_history/house_history/index.html U.S. House of Representatives: House History]\n*[https://www.senate.gov/pagelayout/reference/two_column_table/stats_and_lists.htm U.S. Senate: Statistics and Lists]\n* {{cite book |title=Congressional Directory for the 26th Congress, 1st Session |url= https://books.google.com/?id=VtfC1aNc2VIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false }}\n* {{cite book |title=Congressional Directory for the 26th Congress, 2nd Session |url= https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433091240337&view=1up&seq=5 }}\n{{USCongresses}}\n\n[[Category:26th United States Congress| ]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohn Robinson(link changed toJohn McCracken Robinson) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/26th_United_States_Congress"}
{"title_page": "MG 151 cannon", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{expert needed|date=September 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name= MG 151/15\n|image= \n|caption= \n|origin=[[Nazi Germany]]\n|type= Aircraft Cannon\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged= Yes\n|is_bladed=\n|is_explosive=\n|is_artillery=\n|is_vehicle=\n|is_UK=\n<!-- Service history -->\n|service=\n|used_by=\n|wars= [[World War II]]<br />[[Algerian War]]<br />[[Portuguese Colonial War]]<br />[[Rhodesian Bush War]]\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=\n|design_date=\n|manufacturer= Waffenfabrik Mauser AG\n|production_date=\n|number=\n|variants=\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight= 42.7&nbsp;kg\n|length=\n|part_length=\n|width=\n|height=\n|crew=\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge= 15\u00d796mm cartridge\n|caliber= 15 mm\n|action=\n|rate= 680 to 740&nbsp;rpm\n|velocity= 850&nbsp;m/s{{sfnp|Johnson|1944|pp=384\u2013385}}\n|range=\n|max_range=\n|feed=\n|sights=\n}}\n\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name= MG 151/20\n| image= Mauser MG 151.JPG\n| image_size = 250\n|caption= MG 151/20\n|origin= [[Nazi Germany]]\n|type= Aircraft Cannon\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged= Yes\n|is_bladed=\n|is_explosive=\n|is_artillery=\n|is_vehicle=\n|is_UK=\n<!-- Service history -->\n|service=\n|used_by=[[#Users|See ''users'']]\n|wars= [[World War II]]<br />[[Algerian War]]<br />[[Rhodesian Bush War]]\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=\n|design_date=\n|manufacturer= Waffenfabrik Mauser AG\n|production_date=\n|number=\n|variants=\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight= 42&nbsp;kg\n|length= 1.76 meters\n|part_length=\n|width=\n|height=\n|crew=\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge= [[20\u00d782mm]] cartridge\n|caliber= 20 mm\n|action=\n|rate= 600\u2013750&nbsp;rpm\n|velocity= {{convert|700|m/s|ft/s}} to {{convert|785|m/s|ft/s}}{{sfnp|Johnson|1944|pp=384\u2013385}}{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=165}}\n|range=\n|max_range=\n|feed=\n|sights=\n}}\n\nThe '''MG 151 (MG 151/15)''' was a '''15&nbsp;mm''' aircraft-mounted [[autocannon]] produced by [[Waffenfabrik Mauser]] during [[World War II]].  Its 20mm variant, the '''20&nbsp;mm MG 151/20''' cannon, was widely used on German [[Luftwaffe]] [[Fighter aircraft|fighters]], [[night fighter]]s, [[fighter-bomber]]s, [[bomber]]s and [[ground-attack aircraft]].  Salvaged guns saw post-war use by other nations.\n\n== Development and wartime history (MG 151/20)==\nThe pre-war German doctrine for arming single-engine [[fighter aircraft]] mirrored that of the French. This doctrine favored a powerful autocannon mounted between the cylinder banks of a [[V engine]] and firing through the propeller hub, known as a ''moteur-canon'' in French (from its first use with the [[Hispano-Suiza 8#Variants|Hispano-Suiza HS.8C engine]] in World War I, on the [[SPAD S.XII]]) and by the cognate ''Motorkanone'' in German by the 1930s. The weapon preferred by the French in this role was the most powerful 20mm Oerlikon of the time, namely the [[Oerlikon 20 mm cannon|FFS]] model, but this proved too big for German engines. Mauser was given the task of developing a gun that would fit, with a minimum sacrifice in performance. (As a stop-gap measure, the [[MG FF cannon]] was developed and put in widespread use, but its performance was lackluster.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=161\u2013162}})\n\nProduction of the MG 151 in its original 15&nbsp;mm calibre format began in 1940.  After combat evaluation of the 15&nbsp;mm cartridge as the main armament of early [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]F-2 fighters, the cannon was redesigned as the 20&nbsp;mm MG 151/20 in 1941 to fire a 20&nbsp;mm cartridge. Combat experience showed that a more powerful explosive shell was preferable to a higher projectile velocity.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=165}} The MG 151/20 cartridge was created by expanding the neck of the cartridge to hold the larger explosive [[Shell (projectile)|shell]] used in the [[MG FF cannon]], and shortening the length of the cartridge case holding the longer 20&nbsp;mm shell to match the overall length of the original 15&nbsp;mm cartridge.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=165}} These measures simplified conversion of the 15&nbsp;mm to the 20&nbsp;mm MG 151/20, requiring only a change of barrel and other small modifications.  A disadvantage of the simplified conversion was reduction of projectile [[muzzle velocity]] from {{convert|850|m/s}} for the 15&nbsp;mm shell to {{convert|700|m/s}} for the larger and heavier 20&nbsp;mm shell.{{sfnp|Johnson|1944|pp=384\u2013385}} With an AP projectile the new 20 mm cartridge could penetrate only around 10\u201312 mm of armor at 300 m and at 60 degrees, compared to 18 mm penetration for its 15 mm predecessor in the same conditions but this was not seen as a significant limitation.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=165}} The 20&nbsp;mm version thus became the standard inboard cannon from the Bf 109F-4 series.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=165}} The 20&nbsp;mm MG 151/20 offered more predictable trajectory, longer range and higher impact velocity than the {{convert|580|m/s}} cartridge of the earlier MG FF cannon.{{sfnp|Johnson|1944|pp=384\u2013385}} The MG FF was retained for flexible, wing and upward firing ''[[Schr\u00e4ge Musik]]'' mounts to the end of the war.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=163}}\n\nThe German preference for explosion rather than armor penetration was taken further with the development of the ''[[Minengescho\u00df]]'' ammunition, first introduced for the MG FF (in the Bf&nbsp;109&nbsp;E-4) and later introduced for the MG 151/20. Even this improvement in explosive power turned out to be unsatisfactory against the four-engine bombers that German fighters were up against in the second part of the war. By German calculations, it took about 15\u201320 hits with the MG 151/20 to down a heavy bomber but this was reduced to just 3\u20134 hits for a 30&nbsp;mm shell, from the [[Brisance|shattering]] effects of the [[RDX|hexogen]] explosive in the shells used for both the long-barreled [[MK 103 cannon|MK 103]] and shorter barreled [[MK 108 cannon]]. Only 4\u20135 hits with 20&nbsp;mm calibre cannon were needed for frontal attacks on four-engined bombers but such attacks were difficult to execute. The 30&nbsp;mm MK 108 cannon thus replaced the MG 151/20 as the standard, engine-mount  ''Motorkanone'' centre-line armament starting with the Bf&nbsp;109&nbsp;K-4 and was also retrofitted to some of the G-series.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=166\u2013167}}\n\nEight hundred MG 151/20 exported to Japan aboard the Italian submarine {{ship|Italian submarine|Comandante Cappellini||2}} in August 1943 were used to equip 388 [[Imperial Japanese Army Air Force|Japanese]] [[Kawasaki Ki-61]]-I Hei fighters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.markkaiser.com/japaneseaviation/hien.html |title=Ki-61 Hien survey |last=Kaiser |first=Mark |date=1999 |website=Japanese Aviation |access-date=2009-06-04 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731101040/http://www.markkaiser.com/japaneseaviation/hien.html |archive-date=2009-07-31}}</ref> The 20&nbsp;mm MG 151/20 was also fitted on the [[Macchi C.205]], the [[Fiat G.55]] and [[Reggiane Re.2005]] of the [[Regia Aeronautica]] and [[IAR 80#IAR.81|IAR 81B and 81C]] of the Romanian Royal Air Force.{{sfnp|Williams|Gustin|2003|pp=238, 274\u2013275}}\n\n[[File:MG151 and MG151-20 variants from German Manual, 1942.jpg|thumb|The MG151/20 and MG151/15 variants with a normal (left) and electric (right) ignition.]]\n\n===Postwar Use===\n[[File:20 TorKK MG-151 2 Torpin Tykit 3.JPG|thumb|Two MG 151/20 cannon fitted to a Finnish ''TorKK MG-151 2'' anti-aircraft mounting. Cannons of Torp museum (2011)]]\nAfter World War II, numbers of ex-Luftwaffe MG 151/20 cannon were removed from inventory and from scrapped aircraft and used by various nations in their own aircraft. The [[French Air Force]] (AdA) and [[French Army Light Aviation|French Army aviation arm]] (ALAT) used MG 151/20 cannon as fixed and flexible armament in various aircraft, including helicopters. The AdA and ALAT jointly developed a rubber-insulated flexible mount for the MG 151/20 for use as a door gun, which was later used in combat in Algeria aboard several FAF/ALAT [[Piasecki H-21|H-21C]] assault transport helicopters and on [[Sikorsky H-34#France|Sikorsky HSS-1 Pirate]] gunship helicopters.{{sfnp|Windrow|1997|pp=43}} French Matra MG 151 20mm cannons were used by Portugal and [[Rhodesia]] fitted to their [[Alouette III]] helicopters, while [[Denel]] designed its own variant for the [[South African Air Force]].{{sfnp|Petter-Bowyer|2005|pp=278\u2013279}}<ref name=SAAF>{{cite web |url=http://www.saairforce.co.za/the-airforce/weapons/42/ga-1-20mm-cannon |title=GA 1 20mm Cannon |website=SAAF: Unofficial Website of the South African Air Force |accessdate=2013-06-18}}</ref>\n\n==Users==\n*{{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}<ref name=ZA>{{cite journal |url=http://www.quarry.nildram.co.uk/an_introduction_to_collecting_20.htm |title=An Introduction to Collecting 20 mm Cannon Cartridges |journal=The Cartridge Researcher |first=Anthony G. |last=Williams |date=February 2007 |publisher=European Cartridge Research Association |accessdate=2013-06-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025121852/http://www.quarry.nildram.co.uk/an_introduction_to_collecting_20.htm |archivedate=2012-10-25 |via=Military Guns & Ammunition}}</ref>\n*{{flagcountry|Finland}}\n*{{flagcountry|France}}<ref name=ZA/>\n*{{flag|Italian Social Republic}}\n*{{flag|Empire of Japan|1943}}\n*{{flagcountry|Portugal}}\n*{{flagcountry|Romania}}\n*{{flagcountry|Rhodesia}}{{sfnp|Petter-Bowyer|2005|pp=278\u2013279}}\n*{{flagcountry|South Africa|1928}}<ref name=ZA/>\n\n==MG 151 specifications==\n*Type: single-barrel automatic cannon\n*Caliber: 15\u00d796mm\n*Operation: [[Recoil operation|Recoil-operated]]; [[short recoil]]\n*Length: 1916&nbsp;mm\n*Barrel length: 1254&nbsp;mm\n*Rifling: 8 grooves, right hand twist, 1 turn in 16\"\n*Weight (complete): 38.1&nbsp;kg (84&nbsp;lb)\n*Rate of fire: 740&nbsp;rpm\n*Effective range: 1000&nbsp;m\n*Muzzle velocity: 850&nbsp;m/s (AP-T); 960&nbsp;m/s (HE-T, HEI-T); 1030&nbsp;m/s AP(WC)\n*Projectile types:\n**AP-T weighing 72&nbsp;g\n**HE weighing 57&nbsp;g. HE filler: 2.8&nbsp;g\n**AP(WC) weighing 52&nbsp;g\n\n==MG 151/20 specifications==\nTwo versions of the 20&nbsp;mm MG 151 were built.  Early guns used a percussion priming system, and later E-models used electrical priming. Some rounds were available with a timer self-destruct and/or tracer (or glowtracer). There were also different types of high-explosive shell fillings with either standard [[PETN]], a mixture called HA41 ([[RDX]] and [[aluminium]]), and a compressed version where more explosives were compressed into same space using large pressures (XM).\n\n*Type: single-barrel automatic cannon\n*Caliber: [[20\u00d782mm]]\n*Operation: [[Recoil operation|Recoil-operated]]; [[short recoil]]\n*Length: 1766&nbsp;mm\n*Barrel length: 1104&nbsp;mm/55 calibers\n*Rifling: 1 turn in 23 calibers\n*Weight (complete): 42.7&nbsp;kg (94.1 lbs)\n*Rate of fire: 750&nbsp;rpm\n*Effective range:800&nbsp;m\n*Muzzle velocity: 805&nbsp;m/s (M-Geschoss); 705&nbsp;m/s (HE-T, AP)\n*Round types:\n\n==Ammunition specifications==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-----\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">German Designation</span>\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">US Abbreviation</span>\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">Projectile Weight [g]</span>\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">Bursting charge [g]</span>\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">Muzzle Velocity [m/s]</span>\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">Description</span>\n|-----\n| Brandsprenggranatpatrone 151 mit L'spur ohne Zerleger || HEI-T || align=\"center\" | 113\n| align=\"center\" | 2.3&nbsp;g HE ([[PETN]]) + <br />2.1&nbsp;g incendiary ([[Elektron (alloy)|Elektron]])\n| align=\"center\" | 705 || Nose [[fuze]], tracer, no self-destruct\n|-----\n| Brandgranatpatrone 151  || incendiary || align=\"center\" | 117\n| align=\"center\" | 6.6 to 7.3&nbsp;g incendiary ([[Barium nitrate|BaNO<sub>3</sub>]]+[[Aluminum|Al]]+[[Magnesium|Mg)]]\n| align=\"center\" | ? || Nose fuze\n|-----\n| Minengeschosspatrone 151 ohne L'Spur || HE || align=\"center\" | 95\n| align=\"center\" | 18.6&nbsp;g HE ([[PETN]])\n| align=\"center\" | 805 || Nose fuze, no tracer\n|-\n|Minengeschosspatrone X 151 ohne L'Spur<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://michaelhiske.de/Wehrmacht/Luft/HandbuchBordwaffenMunition/Teil05/Blatt084.htm |title=Handbuch Bordwaffenmunition, Teil 5: 2 cm Munition; 2 cm M-Gesch.Patr. 151 El. o. Zerl. |website=michaelhiske.de |language=de |access-date=2019-02-01}}{{Unreliable source?|date=February 2019}}</ref>\n|HE\n|104\n|25&nbsp;g HE (Ha-41)\n|705\n|Nose fuze, no tracer\n|-----\n| Panzergranatpatrone 151 mit L'spur ohne Zerleger || AP-T || align=\"center\" | 117\n| align=\"center\" | none (bakelite filling in cavity)\n| align=\"center\" | 705 || No fuze, tracer, no self-destruct.<br />Penetration 13mm steel at 60-degree impact, 100m range.\n|-----\n| Panzersprenggranatpatrone 151  || APHE || align=\"center\" | 115\n| align=\"center\" | 4&nbsp;g HE ([[PETN]])\n| align=\"center\" | ? || Detonation after 5mm steel penetration.\n|-----\n| Panzerbrandgranatpatrone (Phosphor) 151 ohne Zerleger || API || align=\"center\" | 115\n| align=\"center\" | 3.6&nbsp;g incendiary ([[White phosphorus|WP]])\n| align=\"center\" | 720 || No fuze, no self-destruct.<br />Penetration 3 to 15mm of steel.\n|-----\n| Panzerbrandgranatpatrone (Elektron) 151 ohne Zerleger || API || align=\"center\" | 117\n| align=\"center\" | 6.2&nbsp;g incendiary (Elektron)\n| align=\"center\" | 695 || Optimized for strafing unarmoured ships. No self-destruct. Penetration 15&nbsp;mm of steel at 75-degree impact angle, 100&nbsp;m range.<br />Fuze functions after 4&nbsp;mm steel penetration.\n|}\n\n== US derivative ==\nDuring World War II the US Army produced the .60-caliber T17, a reverse-engineered copy of the German MG151 chambered for an experimental anti-tank rifle round. A speculative order of 5,000 T17 guns was placed but only around 300 of them were built. However none saw service despite the availability of 6 million rounds of .60 caliber ammunition.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=154}} Almost one million rounds were fired during the T17 testing program. The main US version produced, the T17E3, was made by [[Frigidaire]]; it weighed {{convert|134|lb|kg|abbr=on}} and had a rate of fire of only 600 rounds per minute. Further refinements led to the T39 and T51 versions, but these also did not enter service.{{sfnp|Chinn|1951|pp=105\u2013153}}\n\n===Ammunition===\nA cartridge originally based on an armor-piercing round designed in 1939 for use with the experimental T1 and T1E1 anti-tank rifles. It was cancelled in 1944 when it became clear that modern tanks had armor too thick to penetrate with a heavy rifle cartridge. Developments showed that [[Monroe effect|shaped-charged]] [[M9 rifle grenade|rifle grenades]] and [[Bazooka|rocket launchers]] were the future of infantry anti-tank weapons and the anti-tank rifle concept was abandoned. \n\nMuch like the British attempts to turn their stocks of obsolete .55 Boys anti-tank cartridges into a native-designed heavy machinegun cartridge, the .60-caliber cartridge was repurposed as an auto-cannon cartridge to succeed the older .50 Browning. The ammunition and the T17 cannon were produced from 1942 to 1946 but never proved a substantial improvement over the .50 Browning and the M2HB and M3 heavy machineguns. The cartridge was later shortened and necked-up to produce the 20x102mm Vulcan autocannon round.\n  \n*'''.60 Armor-Piercing (15.2 x 114mm T1E1)''' - A 1180 grain (76.5 gram) kinetic penetrator projectile with a velocity of 3,600 feet per second (1,100 m/s) for a muzzle energy of over 34,000 ft./lbs. (46 kilojoules).<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.quarryhs.co.uk/ATRart.htm |title=An Introduction to Anti-Tank Rifle Cartridges |first=Anthony G. |last=Williams |journal=The Cartridge Researcher |date=December 2004 |publisher=European Cartridge Research Association |accessdate=2013-06-18 |via=Military Guns & Ammunition}} (Modified January 2013, with thanks to Szymon Sztetner.)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://weaponsman.com/?p=29717 |title=The American Cal. .60 Anti-Tank Rifle, T1 & T1E1 |date=February 2016 |website=WeaponsMan |access-date=26 October 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312182716/http://weaponsman.com/?p=29717 |archive-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n*'''.60 T32 Ball (15.2 x 114mm T17)'''\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of weapons of military aircraft of Germany during World War II]]\n*[[MK 108 cannon|MK 108 30 mm cannon]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/TheMachineGunVolume3ByGeorgeMChinn/page/n135 |chapter=Chapter 4: Ordnance Corps Short-Recoil-Operated Automatic Machine Gun |last=Chinn |first=George M. |author-link=George M. Chinn |date=1951 |title=The Machine Gun |volume=III |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office]]}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Johnson |first=Melvin M., Jr. |author-link=Melvin Johnson |date=1944 |title=Rifles and Machine Guns |location=New York |publisher=[[William Morrow & Company]]}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Petter-Bowyer |first=Peter J. H. |date=2005 |title=Winds of Destruction: The Autobiography of a Rhodesian Combat Pilot |location=Johannesburg |publisher=30\u00b0 South |isbn=0-9584890-3-3}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Williams |first=Anthony G. |date=2002 |title=Rapid Fire: The Development of Automatic Cannon, Heavy Machine-Guns and Their Ammunition for Armies, Navies and Air Forces |location=Shrewsbury |publisher=Airlife |isbn=978-1-84037-435-3}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Williams |first1=Anthony G. |last2=Gustin |first2=Emmanuel |date=2003 |title=Flying Guns WWII |location=Shrewsbury |publisher=Airlife |isbn=978-1-84037-227-4}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Windrow |first=Martin |date=1997 |title=The Algerian War, 1954-62 |series=Men-at Arms (No.312) |location=London |publisher=[[Osprey Publishing]] |isbn=978-1-85532-658-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|MG 151}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.saairforce.co.za/the-airforce/weapons/16/type-151-20mm-cannon |title=Type 151 20mm Cannon |website=SAAF: Unofficial Website of the South African Air Force}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.saairforce.co.za/the-airforce/weapons/42/ga-1-20mm-cannon |title=GA 1 20mm Cannon |website=SAAF: Unofficial Website of the South African Air Force}}\n*{{cite journal |url=http://www.lonesentry.com/articles/ttt/mg151-aircraft-weapon-ww2.html |title=German MG-151 Type 15- and 20-mm Aircraft Weapons |date=July 29, 1943 |journal=Tactical and Technical Trends |number=30 |pages=18\u201320 |via=LoneSentry.com}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.wehrtechnikmuseum.de/Exponate/Artillerie/k-020MG151Dr.JPG |title=20 mm MG 151 |website=Museum f\u00fcr historische Wehrtechnik}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.prinzeugen.com/Weapons.htm |title=Weapons and Tactics |website=PrinzEugen.com Schnellboot Archive}}\n*{{cite book |last=Lepage |first=Jean-Denis G. G. |title=Aircraft of the Luftwaffe, 1935-1945: An Illustrated Guide |page=53 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hdQBTcscxyQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Aircrafts+of+the+Luftwaffe&ei=MaChS7X1BIqCyATijfTMBA&cd=1&hl=en#v=onepage&q=&f=false |date=23 March 2009 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-7864-5280-4}}\n\n{{WWIIGermanAerialWeapons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mg 151 Cannon}}\n[[Category:Autocannon]]\n[[Category:Aircraft guns]]\n[[Category:20 mm artillery]]\n[[Category:World War II machine guns]]\n[[Category:World War II artillery of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{expert needed|date=September 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name= MG 151/15\n|image= \n|caption= \n|origin=[[Nazi Germany]]\n|type= Aircraft Cannon\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged= Yes\n|is_bladed=\n|is_explosive=\n|is_artillery=\n|is_vehicle=\n|is_UK=\n<!-- Service history -->\n|service=\n|used_by=\n|wars= [[World War II]]<br />[[Algerian War]]<br />[[Portuguese Colonial War]]<br />[[Rhodesian Bush War]]\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=\n|design_date=\n|manufacturer= Waffenfabrik Mauser AG\n|production_date=\n|number=\n|variants=\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight= 42.7&nbsp;kg\n|length=\n|part_length=\n|width=\n|height=\n|crew=\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge= 15\u00d796mm cartridge\n|caliber= 15 mm\n|action=\n|rate= 680 to 740&nbsp;rpm\n|velocity= 850&nbsp;m/s{{sfnp|Johnson|1944|pp=384\u2013385}}\n|range=\n|max_range=\n|feed=\n|sights=\n}}\n\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name= MG 151/20\n| image= Mauser MG 151.JPG\n| image_size = 250\n|caption= MG 151/20\n|origin= [[Nazi Germany]]\n|type= Aircraft Cannon\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged= Yes\n|is_bladed=\n|is_explosive=\n|is_artillery=\n|is_vehicle=\n|is_UK=\n<!-- Service history -->\n|service=\n|used_by=[[#Users|See ''users'']]\n|wars= [[World War II]]<br />[[Algerian War]]<br />[[Rhodesian Bush War]]\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=\n|design_date=\n|manufacturer= Waffenfabrik Mauser AG\n|production_date=\n|number=\n|variants=\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight= 42&nbsp;kg\n|length= 1.76 meters\n|part_length=\n|width=\n|height=\n|crew=\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge= [[20\u00d782mm]] cartridge\n|caliber= 20 mm\n|action=\n|rate= 600\u2013750&nbsp;rpm\n|velocity= {{convert|700|m/s|ft/s}} to {{convert|785|m/s|ft/s}}{{sfnp|Johnson|1944|pp=384\u2013385}}{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=165}}\n|range=\n|max_range=\n|feed=\n|sights=\n}}\n\nThe '''MG 151 (MG 151/15)''' was a '''15&nbsp;mm''' aircraft-mounted [[autocannon]] produced by [[Waffenfabrik Mauser]] during [[World War II]].  Its 20mm variant, the '''20&nbsp;mm MG 151/20''' cannon, was widely used on German [[Luftwaffe]] [[Fighter aircraft|fighters]], [[night fighter]]s, [[fighter-bomber]]s, [[bomber]]s and [[ground-attack aircraft]].  Salvaged guns saw post-war use by other nations.\n\n== Development and wartime history (MG 151/20)==\nThe pre-war German doctrine for arming single-engine [[fighter aircraft]] mirrored that of the French. This doctrine favored a powerful autocannon mounted between the cylinder banks of a [[V engine]] and firing through the propeller hub, known as a ''moteur-canon'' in French (from its first use with the [[Hispano-Suiza 8#Variants|Hispano-Suiza HS.8C engine]] in World War I, on the [[SPAD S.XII]]) and by the cognate ''Motorkanone'' in German by the 1930s. The weapon preferred by the French in this role was the most powerful 20mm Oerlikon of the time, namely the [[Oerlikon 20 mm cannon|FFS]] model, but this proved too big for German engines. Mauser was given the task of developing a gun that would fit, with a minimum sacrifice in performance. (As a stop-gap measure, the [[MG FF cannon]] was developed and put in widespread use, but its performance was lackluster.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=161\u2013162}})\n\nProduction of the MG 151 in its original 15&nbsp;mm calibre format began in 1940.  After combat evaluation of the 15&nbsp;mm cartridge as the main armament of early [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]F-2 fighters, the cannon was redesigned as the 20&nbsp;mm MG 151/20 in 1941 to fire a 20&nbsp;mm cartridge. Combat experience showed that a more powerful explosive shell was preferable to a higher projectile velocity.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=165}} The MG 151/20 cartridge was created by expanding the neck of the cartridge to hold the larger explosive [[Shell (projectile)|shell]] used in the [[MG FF cannon]], and shortening the length of the cartridge case holding the longer 20&nbsp;mm shell to match the overall length of the original 15&nbsp;mm cartridge.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=165}} These measures simplified conversion of the 15&nbsp;mm to the 20&nbsp;mm MG 151/20, requiring only a change of barrel and other small modifications.  A disadvantage of the simplified conversion was reduction of projectile [[muzzle velocity]] from {{convert|850|m/s}} for the 15&nbsp;mm shell to {{convert|700|m/s}} for the larger and heavier 20&nbsp;mm shell.{{sfnp|Johnson|1944|pp=384\u2013385}} With an AP projectile the new 20 mm cartridge could penetrate only around 10\u201312 mm of armor at 300 m and at 60 degrees, compared to 18 mm penetration for its 15 mm predecessor in the same conditions but this was not seen as a significant limitation.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=165}} The 20&nbsp;mm version thus became the standard inboard cannon from the Bf 109F-4 series.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=165}} The 20&nbsp;mm MG 151/20 offered more predictable trajectory, longer range and higher impact velocity than the {{convert|580|m/s}} cartridge of the earlier MG FF cannon.{{sfnp|Johnson|1944|pp=384\u2013385}} The MG FF was retained for flexible, wing and upward firing ''[[Schr\u00e4ge Musik]]'' mounts to the end of the war.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=163}}\n\nThe German preference for explosion rather than armor penetration was taken further with the development of the ''[[Minengescho\u00df]]'' ammunition, first introduced for the MG FF (in the Bf&nbsp;109&nbsp;E-4) and later introduced for the MG 151/20. Even this improvement in explosive power turned out to be unsatisfactory against the four-engine bombers that German fighters were up against in the second part of the war. By German calculations, it took about 15\u201320 hits with the MG 151/20 to down a heavy bomber but this was reduced to just 3\u20134 hits for a 30&nbsp;mm shell, from the [[Brisance|shattering]] effects of the [[RDX|hexogen]] explosive in the shells used for both the long-barreled [[MK 103 cannon|MK 103]] and shorter barreled [[MK 108 cannon]]. Only 4\u20135 hits with 20&nbsp;mm calibre cannon were needed for frontal attacks on four-engined bombers but such attacks were difficult to execute. The 30&nbsp;mm MK 108 cannon thus replaced the MG 151/20 as the standard, engine-mount  ''Motorkanone'' centre-line armament starting with the Bf&nbsp;109&nbsp;K-4 and was also retrofitted to some of the G-series.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=166\u2013167}}\n\nEight hundred MG 151/20 exported to Japan aboard the Italian submarine {{ship|Italian submarine|Comandante Cappellini||2}} in August 1943 were used to equip 388 [[Imperial Japanese Army Air Force|Japanese]] [[Kawasaki Ki-61]]-I Hei fighters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.markkaiser.com/japaneseaviation/hien.html |title=Ki-61 Hien survey |last=Kaiser |first=Mark |date=1999 |website=Japanese Aviation |access-date=2009-06-04 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731101040/http://www.markkaiser.com/japaneseaviation/hien.html |archive-date=2009-07-31}}</ref> The 20&nbsp;mm MG 151/20 was also fitted on the [[Macchi C.205]], the [[Fiat G.55]] and [[Reggiane Re.2005]] of the [[Regia Aeronautica]] and [[IAR 80#IAR.81|IAR 81B and 81C]] of the Romanian Royal Air Force.{{sfnp|Williams|Gustin|2003|pp=238, 274\u2013275}}\n\n[[File:MG151 and MG151-20 variants from German Manual, 1942.jpg|thumb|The MG151/20 and MG151/15 variants with a normal (left) and electric (right) ignition.]]\n\n===Postwar Use===\n[[File:20 TorKK MG-151 2 Torpin Tykit 3.JPG|thumb|Two MG 151/20 cannon fitted to a Finnish ''TorKK MG-151 2'' anti-aircraft mounting. Cannons of Torp museum (2011)]]\nAfter World War II, numbers of ex-Luftwaffe MG 151/20 cannon were removed from inventory and from scrapped aircraft and used by various nations in their own aircraft. The [[French Air Force]] (AdA) and [[French Army Light Aviation|French Army aviation arm]] (ALAT) used MG 151/20 cannon as fixed and flexible armament in various aircraft, including helicopters. The AdA and ALAT jointly developed a rubber-insulated flexible mount for the MG 151/20 for use as a door gun, which was later used in combat in Algeria aboard several FAF/ALAT [[Piasecki H-21|H-21C]] assault transport helicopters and on [[Sikorsky H-34#France|Sikorsky HSS-1 Pirate]] gunship helicopters.{{sfnp|Windrow|1997|pp=43}} French Matra MG 151 20mm cannons were used by Portugal and [[Rhodesia]] fitted to their [[Alouette III]] helicopters, while [[Denel]] designed its own variant for the [[South African Air Force]].{{sfnp|Petter-Bowyer|2005|pp=278\u2013279}}<ref name=SAAF>{{cite web |url=http://www.saairforce.co.za/the-airforce/weapons/42/ga-1-20mm-cannon |title=GA 1 20mm Cannon |website=SAAF: Unofficial Website of the South African Air Force |accessdate=2013-06-18}}</ref>\n\n==Users==\n*{{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}<ref name=ZA>{{cite journal |url=http://www.quarry.nildram.co.uk/an_introduction_to_collecting_20.htm |title=An Introduction to Collecting 20 mm Cannon Cartridges |journal=The Cartridge Researcher |first=Anthony G. |last=Williams |date=February 2007 |publisher=European Cartridge Research Association |accessdate=2013-06-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025121852/http://www.quarry.nildram.co.uk/an_introduction_to_collecting_20.htm |archivedate=2012-10-25 |via=Military Guns & Ammunition}}</ref>\n*{{flagcountry|Finland}}\n*{{flagcountry|France}}<ref name=ZA/>\n*{{flag|Italian Social Republic}}\n*{{flag|Empire of Japan|1943}}\n*{{flagcountry|Portugal}}\n*{{flagcountry|Romania}}\n*{{flagcountry|Rhodesia}}{{sfnp|Petter-Bowyer|2005|pp=278\u2013279}}\n*{{flagcountry|South Africa|1928}}<ref name=ZA/>\n\n==MG 151/15 specifications==\n*Type: single-barrel automatic cannon\n*Caliber: 15\u00d796mm\n*Operation: [[Recoil operation|Recoil-operated]]; [[short recoil]]\n*Length: 1916&nbsp;mm\n*Barrel length: 1254&nbsp;mm\n*Rifling: 8 grooves, right hand twist, 1 turn in 16\"\n*Weight (complete): 38.1&nbsp;kg (84&nbsp;lb)\n*Rate of fire: 740&nbsp;rpm\n*Effective range: 1000&nbsp;m\n*Muzzle velocity: 850&nbsp;m/s (AP-T); 960&nbsp;m/s (HE-T, HEI-T); 1030&nbsp;m/s AP(WC)\n*Projectile types:\n**AP-T weighing 72&nbsp;g\n**HE weighing 57&nbsp;g. HE filler: 2.8&nbsp;g\n**AP(WC) weighing 52&nbsp;g\n\n==MG 151/20 specifications==\nTwo versions of the 20&nbsp;mm MG 151 were built.  Early guns used a percussion priming system, and later E-models used electrical priming. Some rounds were available with a timer self-destruct and/or tracer (or glowtracer). There were also different types of high-explosive shell fillings with either standard [[PETN]], a mixture called HA41 ([[RDX]] and [[aluminium]]), and a compressed version where more explosives were compressed into same space using large pressures (XM).\n\n*Type: single-barrel automatic cannon\n*Caliber: [[20\u00d782mm]]\n*Operation: [[Recoil operation|Recoil-operated]]; [[short recoil]]\n*Length: 1766&nbsp;mm\n*Barrel length: 1104&nbsp;mm/55 calibers\n*Rifling: 1 turn in 23 calibers\n*Weight (complete): 42.7&nbsp;kg (94.1 lbs)\n*Rate of fire: 750&nbsp;rpm\n*Effective range:800&nbsp;m\n*Muzzle velocity: 805&nbsp;m/s (M-Geschoss); 705&nbsp;m/s (HE-T, AP)\n*Round types:\n\n==Ammunition specifications==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-----\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">German Designation</span>\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">US Abbreviation</span>\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">Projectile Weight [g]</span>\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">Bursting charge [g]</span>\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">Muzzle Velocity [m/s]</span>\n! <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">Description</span>\n|-----\n| Brandsprenggranatpatrone 151 mit L'spur ohne Zerleger || HEI-T || align=\"center\" | 113\n| align=\"center\" | 2.3&nbsp;g HE ([[PETN]]) + <br />2.1&nbsp;g incendiary ([[Elektron (alloy)|Elektron]])\n| align=\"center\" | 705 || Nose [[fuze]], tracer, no self-destruct\n|-----\n| Brandgranatpatrone 151  || incendiary || align=\"center\" | 117\n| align=\"center\" | 6.6 to 7.3&nbsp;g incendiary ([[Barium nitrate|BaNO<sub>3</sub>]]+[[Aluminum|Al]]+[[Magnesium|Mg)]]\n| align=\"center\" | ? || Nose fuze\n|-----\n| Minengeschosspatrone 151 ohne L'Spur || HE || align=\"center\" | 95\n| align=\"center\" | 18.6&nbsp;g HE ([[PETN]])\n| align=\"center\" | 805 || Nose fuze, no tracer\n|-\n|Minengeschosspatrone X 151 ohne L'Spur<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://michaelhiske.de/Wehrmacht/Luft/HandbuchBordwaffenMunition/Teil05/Blatt084.htm |title=Handbuch Bordwaffenmunition, Teil 5: 2 cm Munition; 2 cm M-Gesch.Patr. 151 El. o. Zerl. |website=michaelhiske.de |language=de |access-date=2019-02-01}}{{Unreliable source?|date=February 2019}}</ref>\n|HE\n|104\n|25&nbsp;g HE (Ha-41)\n|705\n|Nose fuze, no tracer\n|-----\n| Panzergranatpatrone 151 mit L'spur ohne Zerleger || AP-T || align=\"center\" | 117\n| align=\"center\" | none (bakelite filling in cavity)\n| align=\"center\" | 705 || No fuze, tracer, no self-destruct.<br />Penetration 13mm steel at 60-degree impact, 100m range.\n|-----\n| Panzersprenggranatpatrone 151  || APHE || align=\"center\" | 115\n| align=\"center\" | 4&nbsp;g HE ([[PETN]])\n| align=\"center\" | ? || Detonation after 5mm steel penetration.\n|-----\n| Panzerbrandgranatpatrone (Phosphor) 151 ohne Zerleger || API || align=\"center\" | 115\n| align=\"center\" | 3.6&nbsp;g incendiary ([[White phosphorus|WP]])\n| align=\"center\" | 720 || No fuze, no self-destruct.<br />Penetration 3 to 15mm of steel.\n|-----\n| Panzerbrandgranatpatrone (Elektron) 151 ohne Zerleger || API || align=\"center\" | 117\n| align=\"center\" | 6.2&nbsp;g incendiary (Elektron)\n| align=\"center\" | 695 || Optimized for strafing unarmoured ships. No self-destruct. Penetration 15&nbsp;mm of steel at 75-degree impact angle, 100&nbsp;m range.<br />Fuze functions after 4&nbsp;mm steel penetration.\n|}\n\n== US derivative ==\nDuring World War II the US Army produced the .60-caliber T17, a reverse-engineered copy of the German MG151 chambered for an experimental anti-tank rifle round. A speculative order of 5,000 T17 guns was placed but only around 300 of them were built. However none saw service despite the availability of 6 million rounds of .60 caliber ammunition.{{sfnp|Williams|2002|pp=154}} Almost one million rounds were fired during the T17 testing program. The main US version produced, the T17E3, was made by [[Frigidaire]]; it weighed {{convert|134|lb|kg|abbr=on}} and had a rate of fire of only 600 rounds per minute. Further refinements led to the T39 and T51 versions, but these also did not enter service.{{sfnp|Chinn|1951|pp=105\u2013153}}\n\n===Ammunition===\nA cartridge originally based on an armor-piercing round designed in 1939 for use with the experimental T1 and T1E1 anti-tank rifles. It was cancelled in 1944 when it became clear that modern tanks had armor too thick to penetrate with a heavy rifle cartridge. Developments showed that [[Monroe effect|shaped-charged]] [[M9 rifle grenade|rifle grenades]] and [[Bazooka|rocket launchers]] were the future of infantry anti-tank weapons and the anti-tank rifle concept was abandoned. \n\nMuch like the British attempts to turn their stocks of obsolete .55 Boys anti-tank cartridges into a native-designed heavy machinegun cartridge, the .60-caliber cartridge was repurposed as an auto-cannon cartridge to succeed the older .50 Browning. The ammunition and the T17 cannon were produced from 1942 to 1946 but never proved a substantial improvement over the .50 Browning and the M2HB and M3 heavy machineguns. The cartridge was later shortened and necked-up to produce the 20x102mm Vulcan autocannon round.\n  \n*'''.60 Armor-Piercing (15.2 x 114mm T1E1)''' - A 1180 grain (76.5 gram) kinetic penetrator projectile with a velocity of 3,600 feet per second (1,100 m/s) for a muzzle energy of over 34,000 ft./lbs. (46 kilojoules).<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.quarryhs.co.uk/ATRart.htm |title=An Introduction to Anti-Tank Rifle Cartridges |first=Anthony G. |last=Williams |journal=The Cartridge Researcher |date=December 2004 |publisher=European Cartridge Research Association |accessdate=2013-06-18 |via=Military Guns & Ammunition}} (Modified January 2013, with thanks to Szymon Sztetner.)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://weaponsman.com/?p=29717 |title=The American Cal. .60 Anti-Tank Rifle, T1 & T1E1 |date=February 2016 |website=WeaponsMan |access-date=26 October 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312182716/http://weaponsman.com/?p=29717 |archive-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n*'''.60 T32 Ball (15.2 x 114mm T17)'''\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of weapons of military aircraft of Germany during World War II]]\n*[[MK 108 cannon|MK 108 30 mm cannon]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/TheMachineGunVolume3ByGeorgeMChinn/page/n135 |chapter=Chapter 4: Ordnance Corps Short-Recoil-Operated Automatic Machine Gun |last=Chinn |first=George M. |author-link=George M. Chinn |date=1951 |title=The Machine Gun |volume=III |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office]]}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Johnson |first=Melvin M., Jr. |author-link=Melvin Johnson |date=1944 |title=Rifles and Machine Guns |location=New York |publisher=[[William Morrow & Company]]}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Petter-Bowyer |first=Peter J. H. |date=2005 |title=Winds of Destruction: The Autobiography of a Rhodesian Combat Pilot |location=Johannesburg |publisher=30\u00b0 South |isbn=0-9584890-3-3}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Williams |first=Anthony G. |date=2002 |title=Rapid Fire: The Development of Automatic Cannon, Heavy Machine-Guns and Their Ammunition for Armies, Navies and Air Forces |location=Shrewsbury |publisher=Airlife |isbn=978-1-84037-435-3}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Williams |first1=Anthony G. |last2=Gustin |first2=Emmanuel |date=2003 |title=Flying Guns WWII |location=Shrewsbury |publisher=Airlife |isbn=978-1-84037-227-4}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Windrow |first=Martin |date=1997 |title=The Algerian War, 1954-62 |series=Men-at Arms (No.312) |location=London |publisher=[[Osprey Publishing]] |isbn=978-1-85532-658-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|MG 151}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.saairforce.co.za/the-airforce/weapons/16/type-151-20mm-cannon |title=Type 151 20mm Cannon |website=SAAF: Unofficial Website of the South African Air Force}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.saairforce.co.za/the-airforce/weapons/42/ga-1-20mm-cannon |title=GA 1 20mm Cannon |website=SAAF: Unofficial Website of the South African Air Force}}\n*{{cite journal |url=http://www.lonesentry.com/articles/ttt/mg151-aircraft-weapon-ww2.html |title=German MG-151 Type 15- and 20-mm Aircraft Weapons |date=July 29, 1943 |journal=Tactical and Technical Trends |number=30 |pages=18\u201320 |via=LoneSentry.com}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.wehrtechnikmuseum.de/Exponate/Artillerie/k-020MG151Dr.JPG |title=20 mm MG 151 |website=Museum f\u00fcr historische Wehrtechnik}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.prinzeugen.com/Weapons.htm |title=Weapons and Tactics |website=PrinzEugen.com Schnellboot Archive}}\n*{{cite book |last=Lepage |first=Jean-Denis G. G. |title=Aircraft of the Luftwaffe, 1935-1945: An Illustrated Guide |page=53 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hdQBTcscxyQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Aircrafts+of+the+Luftwaffe&ei=MaChS7X1BIqCyATijfTMBA&cd=1&hl=en#v=onepage&q=&f=false |date=23 March 2009 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-7864-5280-4}}\n\n{{WWIIGermanAerialWeapons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mg 151 Cannon}}\n[[Category:Autocannon]]\n[[Category:Aircraft guns]]\n[[Category:20 mm artillery]]\n[[Category:World War II machine guns]]\n[[Category:World War II artillery of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Costas-1963", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMG 151/15 specifications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MG_151_cannon"}
{"title_page": "Declaration of Religious Harmony", "text_new": "{{short description|State declaration in Singapore}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\nThe '''Declaration of Religious Harmony''' of Singapore is a statement that affirms the importance of, and the commitment of Singaporeans towards, religious harmony. It is a basis for Singaporeans to reflect on religious harmony, and what should be done to achieve it.  \n\nThe idea of having a Code on Religious Harmony was proposed by the then Prime Minister [[Goh Chok Tong]] in September<ref>[http://www.iccc.org.sg/rhwcommittee.html Explanation of the Declaration by the Religious Harmony Working Committee on the website of the International Council of Christian Churches].</ref> or October 2002.<ref>\"[http://archive.rsi.com.sg/en/programmes/newsline/2003/06/10_06_01.htm Declaration of Religious Harmony Becomes Part of Singapore Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060217031111/http://archive.rsi.com.sg/en/programmes/newsline/2003/06/10_06_01.htm |date=17 February 2006 }}\" (10 June 2003), an interview of Eugene Tan, lecturer in law at the Singapore Management University, by Felix Tan on the website of [[Radio Singapore International]].</ref> This followed strains in racial harmony in the country following the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] in the United States of America and the arrest and detention of members of the [[Jemaah Islamiyah]] terrorist network in Singapore in December 2001.\n\nThe Declaration was issued on 9 June 2003 by a working committee chaired by [[Minister of State]] Chan Soo Sen and involving the national bodies of all mainstream religious groups in Singapore, after six months of intense debate over its wording.<ref>{{cite web |title=More than words, a S'pore way of life |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20030610-1.2.2 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=25 September 2019 |date=10 June 2003}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, an [[Inter-Religious Harmony Circle]] (IRHC) comprising representatives of the religious groups involved in the working committee was formed to promote the Declaration. The IRHC has encouraged Singaporeans to recite the Declaration during the week when [[Racial Harmony Day]] (21 July) is marked every year.\n\n==Text of the declaration==\n:We, the people in Singapore, declare that religious harmony is vital for peace, progress and prosperity in our multi-racial and multi-religious Nation.\n\n:We resolve to strengthen religious harmony through mutual tolerance, confidence, respect, and understanding.\n\n:We shall always\n::Recognise the secular nature of our State,\n::Promote cohesion within our society,\n::Respect each other's freedom of religion,\n::Grow our common space while respecting our diversity,\n::Foster inter-religious communications, \n::and thereby ensure that religion will not be abused to create conflict and disharmony in Singapore.\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Inter-racial and religious confidence circle]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.iro.sg/about/declaration/ The text of the Declaration on the website of the Inter-religious Organisation, Singapore].\n\n[[Category:Religion in Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|State declaration in Signapore}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\nThe '''Declaration of Religious Harmony''' of Singapore is a statement that affirms the importance of, and the commitment of Singaporeans towards, religious harmony. It is a basis for Singaporeans to reflect on religious harmony, and what should be done to achieve it.  \n\nThe idea of having a Code on Religious Harmony was proposed by the then Prime Minister [[Goh Chok Tong]] in September<ref>[http://www.iccc.org.sg/rhwcommittee.html Explanation of the Declaration by the Religious Harmony Working Committee on the website of the International Council of Christian Churches].</ref> or October 2002.<ref>\"[http://archive.rsi.com.sg/en/programmes/newsline/2003/06/10_06_01.htm Declaration of Religious Harmony Becomes Part of Singapore Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060217031111/http://archive.rsi.com.sg/en/programmes/newsline/2003/06/10_06_01.htm |date=17 February 2006 }}\" (10 June 2003), an interview of Eugene Tan, lecturer in law at the Singapore Management University, by Felix Tan on the website of [[Radio Singapore International]].</ref> This followed strains in racial harmony in the country following the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] in the United States of America and the arrest and detention of members of the [[Jemaah Islamiyah]] terrorist network in Singapore in December 2001.\n\nThe Declaration was issued on 9 June 2003 by a working committee chaired by [[Minister of State]] Chan Soo Sen and involving the national bodies of all mainstream religious groups in Singapore, after six months of intense debate over its wording.<ref>{{cite web |title=More than words, a S'pore way of life |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20030610-1.2.2 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=25 September 2019 |date=10 June 2003}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, an [[Inter-Religious Harmony Circle]] (IRHC) comprising representatives of the religious groups involved in the working committee was formed to promote the Declaration. The IRHC has encouraged Singaporeans to recite the Declaration during the week when [[Racial Harmony Day]] (21 July) is marked every year.\n\n==Text of the declaration==\n:We, the people in Singapore, declare that religious harmony is vital for peace, progress and prosperity in our multi-racial and multi-religious Nation.\n\n:We resolve to strengthen religious harmony through mutual tolerance, confidence, respect, and understanding.\n\n:We shall always\n::Recognise the secular nature of our State,\n::Promote cohesion within our society,\n::Respect each other's freedom of religion,\n::Grow our common space while respecting our diversity,\n::Foster inter-religious communications, \n::and thereby ensure that religion will not be abused to create conflict and disharmony in Singapore.\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Inter-racial and religious confidence circle]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.iro.sg/about/declaration/ The text of the Declaration on the website of the Inter-religious Organisation, Singapore].\n\n[[Category:Religion in Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declaration_of_Religious_Harmony"}
{"title_page": "Zygmunt Gorgolewski", "text_new": "{{Infobox architect\n| name = Zygmunt Gorgolewski\n| image = Zygmunt Gorgolewski.jpg\n| birth_date = {{Birthdate|1845|2|14}}\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1903|7|6|1845|2|14}}\n| nationality = Polish\n| alma_mater = [[Bauakademie|Royal Building Academy]]\n| occupation = architect\n| practice = \n| significant_buildings = {{Unbulleted list|[[Lviv Theatre of Opera and Ballet]]}}\n| significant_projects = \n}}\n[[Image:Teatr Lwow22.jpg|thumb|right|Grand Theatre in Lviv]]\n\n[[Image:Lw\u00f3w opera projekt elewacji bocznej 1896.png|thumb|right|Side view of the original project]]\n\n'''Zygmunt Gorgolewski''' (February 14, 1845 in [[Solec Kujawski|Solec]] &ndash; July 6, 1903 in [[Lviv]]) was a [[Poland|Polish]] architect, renowned for his construction of the [[Lviv Opera and Ballet Theater|Grand Theatre]] in [[Lviv]].<ref name=\"Lewinski\">{{in lang|pl}} Jakub Lewi\u0144ski. ''Mi\u0119dzy tradycj\u0105, a nowoczesno\u015bci\u0105; Architektura Lwowa lat 1893-1918''. Neriton. 2005. p. 145.</ref><ref>Markian Prokopovych. ''Habsburg Lemberg: architecture, public space, and politics in the Galician capital, 1772-1914''. Purdue University Press. 2009. p. 177</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nGorgolewski was born in [[Solec Kujawski|Solec (Schulitz)]], [[Grand Duchy of Posen]], [[Kingdom of Prussia]]. Between 1866 and 1871 he studied in [[Berlin]] at the [[Bauakademie|Royal Building Academy]]. During his studies, Gorgolewski also supervised the construction of [[Berlin Hauptbahnhof#History|Lehrte Train Station in Berlin]]. After graduating, for six years he worked as an assistant in his alma mater. After that he became an advisor at the Prussian Ministry of Public Works, official royal palace architect and architecture inspector (K\u00f6niglicher Regierungsbaumeister) in [[Halle, Saxony-Anhalt|Halle upon Saale]].<ref name=\"Stanski\">{{in lang|pl}} [http://www.lwow.home.pl/semper/gorgolewski.html Piotr Marek Sta\u0144ski - ''Zygmunt Gorgolewski, tw\u00f3rca gmachu Lwowskiego Teatru Wielkiego'']</ref> Gorgolewski was one of the most notable supporters of [[historicism (architecture)|historicism]] in architecture in the [[Kingdom of Prussia]] and then the [[German Empire]]. \n\n[[File:Badehaus Oeynhausen.jpg|thumb|Bad Oeynhausen: Bathhouse IV (now II), 1883-1885 by Zygmunt Gorgolewski]]\nAmong his projects were two versions of the future [[Reichstag (building)|Reichstag building]], which he proposed in 1872 and then in 1882. His projects were among merely 20 chosen by the committee out of more than 100. However, in the end his ideas for these projects were refused.<ref name=\"Stanski\"/> At the same time, Gorgolewski was awarded with the construction of [[Liebknecht Bridge|Kaiser Wilhelm's Bridge]]. Other, more successful, projects include the plans of refurbishment of royal palaces in Berlin and [[Kiel Castle|in Kiel]], expansion of University Hospitals in Halle upon Saale and [[Bonn]], the Bathhouse IV (1883-1885, now numbered II) of [[Bad Oeynhausen]] spa in [[Province of Westphalia|Westphalia]].<ref>Cf. [https://bad-driburg.teutoburgerwald.de/ausflugsziel/badehaus-ii-im-kurpark-bad-oeynhausen ''Badehaus II im Kurpark, Bad Oeynhausen''], retrieved on 10 April 2020.</ref> In addition, he contributed plans for the projected new construction of the [[Berlin Cathedral|Berlin Supreme Parish and Collegiate Church]], and worked on renovating [[Bellevue Palace (Germany)|Bellevue Palace]], and created as main architect courthouses in [[Opole|Opole (Oppeln)]] and [[Olsztyn|Olsztyn (Allenstein)]], as well as prisons in [[\u015awidnica|\u015awidnica (Schweidnitz)]] and [[Chorz\u00f3w|Chorz\u00f3w (K\u00f6nigsh\u00fctte)]]. \n\nIn the [[Greater Poland]] region, Gorgolewski conducted the construction of many notable palaces both in and around [[Pozna\u0144]]. His works include:<ref name=\"Stanski\"/>\n* refurbishment of a church in [[Wrze\u015bnia]]\n* refurbishment of [[Dzia\u0142y\u0144ski]] family palace in [[Go\u0142uch\u00f3w, Greater Poland Voivodeship|Go\u0142uch\u00f3w]]\n* refurbishment of [[Dzia\u0142y\u0144ski]] family library in [[K\u00f3rnik]]\n* construction of [[Twardowski]] family palace in [[Kobylniki, Szamotu\u0142y County|Kobylniki]]<ref>Krystyna Siemiatycka. ''Polish Palaces''. [http://kobylniki.pl/index_ang.php?go=historia The History of the Palace in Kobylniki] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425162410/http://kobylniki.pl/index_ang.php?go=historia |date=April 25, 2012 }}</ref>\n* enlargement of [[Kwilecki]] palace in [[Opor\u00f3w]]\n* [[Radziwill|Radziwi\u0142\u0142]] family romantic castle ''Bagatela'' near [[Ostr\u00f3w Wielkopolski]]\n* construction of a new church tower as well as a [[Czapski]] family chapel in Smogulec\n* construction of the headquarters of the [[Pozna\u0144 Society of Friends of Arts and Sciences]] (1874\u201379), as well as houses in Berli\u0144ska street in front of it.\n\nHe was also appointed as the main architect of the refurbishment of the palace of [[Ferdynand Radziwi\u0142\u0142]] in [[O\u0142yka]], [[Volhynia]]. During his stay there, Gorgolewski for the first time visited [[Vilnius]], [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kiev]] and [[Lviv]].<ref name=\"Stanski\"/> The latter city enjoyed a period of fast expansion and in 1875 Gorgolewski took part in the contest for the project of the future [[Diet of Galicia and Lodomeria]]. His project was the most disputed and highly praised, but it was finally turned down, mostly due to financial reasons. \n\nIn 1879, Gorgolewski married Helena n\u00e9e Hulewicz. He was also an active member of many architectural juries across partitioned Poland. Among others, he was the member of the jury during the contest for the project of [[Teatr Stary|Krak\u00f3w Old Theatre]] (1889),<ref>\u201ePreisangaben\u201c, in: ''[[Deutsche Bauzeitung]]'', No.&nbsp;9 (30&nbsp;January 1889), vol.&nbsp;XXIII, p.&nbsp;60.</ref> the bank in [[Czerniowce]] and [[Church of St.&nbsp;Elizabeth, Lviv|Church of St. Elizabeth in Lviv]]. In 1893 he moved to Lviv, where he was chosen as the main architect of the Grand Theatre (1897\u20131900). To avoid being accused of using his well-established position in society, Gorgolewski prepared his winning project of the theatre in secret<ref name=\"Stanski\"/> and then sent it under a [[Pseudonym|false name]] from [[Leipzig]]. Other notable building of his authorship was the Industrial School in the same city.\n\nGorgolewski died in Lviv and was buried in the [[Lychakiv Cemetery]].<ref name=\"Stanski\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=200 heights=160>\nImage:LvivOperaHouse2013.JPG|Lviv Theatre of Opera and Ballet\nImage:Pa\u0142ac wybudowany dla ordynata Tadeusza Twardowskiego 01.JPG|[[Kobylniki, Szamotu\u0142y County|Kobylniki]] Palace\nImage:Siedziba Pozna\u0144skiego Towarzystwa Przyjaci\u00f3\u0142 Nauk.jpg|Seat of the Pozna\u0144 Society of Friends of Arts and Sciences\nImage:Lwow-grobGorgolewskiego.jpg|Tomb of the Gorgolewski family in Lviv\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Lviv]]\n*[[Teodor Talowski]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gorgolewski, Zygmunt}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Solec Kujawski]]\n[[Category:Polish architects]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Posen]]\n[[Category:Architects from Lviv]]\n[[Category:Burials at Lychakiv Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox architect\n| name = Zygmunt Gorgolewski\n| image = Zygmunt Gorgolewski.jpg\n| birth_date = {{Birthdate|1845|2|14}}\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1903|7|6|1845|2|14}}\n| nationality = Polish\n| alma_mater = [[Bauakademie|Royal Building Academy]]\n| occupation = architect\n| practice = \n| significant_buildings = {{Unbulleted list|[[Lviv Theatre of Opera and Ballet]]}}\n| significant_projects = \n}}\n[[Image:Teatr Lwow22.jpg|thumb|right|Grand Theatre in Lviv]]\n\n[[Image:Lw\u00f3w opera projekt elewacji bocznej 1896.png|thumb|right|Side view of the original project]]\n\n'''Zygmunt Gorgolewski''' (February 14, 1845 in [[Solec Kujawski|Solec]] &ndash; July 6, 1903 in [[Lviv]]) was a [[Poland|Polish]] architect, renowned for his construction of the [[Lviv Opera and Ballet Theater|Grand Theatre]] in [[Lviv]].<ref name=\"Lewinski\">{{in lang|pl}} Jakub Lewi\u0144ski. ''Mi\u0119dzy tradycj\u0105, a nowoczesno\u015bci\u0105; Architektura Lwowa lat 1893-1918''. Neriton. 2005. p. 145.</ref><ref>Markian Prokopovych. ''Habsburg Lemberg: architecture, public space, and politics in the Galician capital, 1772-1914''. Purdue University Press. 2009. p. 177</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nGorgolewski was born in [[Solec Kujawski|Solec (Schulitz)]], [[Province of Posen]], [[Kingdom of Prussia]]. Between 1866 and 1871 he studied in [[Berlin]] at the [[Bauakademie|Royal Building Academy]]. During his studies, Gorgolewski also supervised the construction of Hanover Train Station in Berlin. After graduating, for six years he worked as an assistant in his alma mater. After that he became an advisor at the German Ministry of Public Works, official royal palace architect and architecture inspector in [[Halle, Saxony-Anhalt|Halle]].<ref name=\"Stanski\">{{in lang|pl}} [http://www.lwow.home.pl/semper/gorgolewski.html Piotr Marek Sta\u0144ski - ''Zygmunt Gorgolewski, tw\u00f3rca gmachu Lwowskiego Teatru Wielkiego'']</ref> Gorgolewski was one of the most notable supporters of [[historicism (architecture)|historicism]] in architecture in the [[Kingdom of Prussia]] and then the [[German Empire]]. \n\nAmong his projects were two versions of the future [[Reichstag (building)|Reichstag]] building, which he proposed in 1872 and then in 1882. His projects were among merely 20 chosen by the committee out of more than 100. However, in the end his ideas for these projects were refused.<ref name=\"Stanski\"/> At the same time, Gorgolewski was awarded with the construction of Kaiser Wilhelm's Bridge. Other, more successful, projects include the plans of refurbishment of royal palaces in Berlin and [[Kiel]], expansion of University Hospitals in Halle and [[Bonn]], expansion of [[Bad Oeynhausen]] spa in [[Province of Westphalia|Westphalia]]. In addition, he was the main architect of the Protestant cathedral in Berlin, [[Belle Vue (Palace)|Belle Vue]] palace, courthouses in [[Opole|Opole (Oppeln)]] and [[Olsztyn|Olsztyn (Allenstein)]], as well as prisons in [[\u015awidnica|\u015awidnica (Schweidnitz)]] and [[Chorz\u00f3w|Chorz\u00f3w (K\u00f6nigsh\u00fctte)]]. \n\nIn the [[Greater Poland]] region, Gorgolewski conducted the construction of many notable palaces both in and around [[Pozna\u0144]]. His works include:<ref name=\"Stanski\"/>\n* refurbishment of a church in [[Wrze\u015bnia]]\n* refurbishment of [[Dzia\u0142y\u0144ski]] family palace in [[Go\u0142uch\u00f3w, Greater Poland Voivodeship|Go\u0142uch\u00f3w]]\n* refurbishment of [[Dzia\u0142y\u0144ski]] family library in [[K\u00f3rnik]]\n* construction of [[Twardowski]] family palace in [[Kobylniki, Szamotu\u0142y County|Kobylniki]]<ref>Krystyna Siemiatycka. ''Polish Palaces''. [http://kobylniki.pl/index_ang.php?go=historia The History of the Palace in Kobylniki] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425162410/http://kobylniki.pl/index_ang.php?go=historia |date=April 25, 2012 }}</ref>\n* enlargement of [[Kwilecki]] palace in [[Opor\u00f3w]]\n* [[Radziwill|Radziwi\u0142\u0142]] family romantic castle ''Bagatela'' near [[Ostr\u00f3w Wielkopolski]]\n* construction of a new church tower as well as a [[Czapski]] family chapel in Smogulec\n* construction of the headquarters of the [[Pozna\u0144 Society of Friends of Arts and Sciences]] (1874\u201379), as well as houses in Berli\u0144ska street in front of it.\n\nHe was also appointed as the main architect of the refurbishment of the palace of [[Ferdynand Radziwi\u0142\u0142]] in [[O\u0142yka]], [[Volhynia]]. During his stay there, Gorgolewski for the first time visited [[Vilnius]], [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kiev]] and [[Lviv]].<ref name=\"Stanski\"/> The latter city enjoyed a period of fast expansion and in 1875 Gorgolewski took part in the contest for the project of the future [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Galician]] [[Sejm]]. His project was the most disputed and highly praised, but it was finally turned down, mostly due to financial reasons. \n\nIn 1879, Gorgolewski married Helena ''n\u00e9e'' Hulewicz. He was also an active member of many architectural juries across partitioned Poland. Among others, he was the member of the jury during the contest for the project of [[Teatr Stary|Krak\u00f3w Old Theatre]] (1889), the bank in [[Czerniowce]] and [[Church of St. Elizabeth, Lviv|Church of St. Elizabeth in Lviv]]. In 1893 he moved to Lviv, where he was chosen as the main architect of the Grand Theatre (1897\u20131900). To avoid being accused of using his well-established position in society, Gorgolewski prepared his winning project of the theatre in secret<ref name=\"Stanski\"/> and then sent it under a [[Pseudonym|false name]] from [[Leipzig]]. Other notable building of his authorship was the Industrial School in the same city.\n\nGorgolewski died in Lviv and was buried in the [[Lychakiv Cemetery]].<ref name=\"Stanski\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=200 heights=160>\nImage:LvivOperaHouse2013.JPG|Lviv Theatre of Opera and Ballet\nImage:Pa\u0142ac wybudowany dla ordynata Tadeusza Twardowskiego 01.JPG|[[Kobylniki, Szamotu\u0142y County|Kobylniki]] Palace\nImage:Siedziba Pozna\u0144skiego Towarzystwa Przyjaci\u00f3\u0142 Nauk.jpg|Seat of the Pozna\u0144 Society of Friends of Arts and Sciences\nImage:Lwow-grobGorgolewskiego.jpg|Tomb of the Gorgolewski family in Lviv\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Lviv]]\n*[[Teodor Talowski]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gorgolewski, Zygmunt}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Solec Kujawski]]\n[[Category:Polish architects]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Posen]]\n[[Category:Architects from Lviv]]\n[[Category:Burials at Lychakiv Cemetery]]\n", "name_user": "Ulf Heinsohn", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and career:+lks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zygmunt_Gorgolewski"}
{"title_page": "Fanny Mendelssohn", "text_new": "{{short description|19th-century German pianist and composer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Fanny Mendelssohn\n| image              = Fanny Hensel 1842.jpg\n| caption            = Fanny Hensel, 1842, by [[Moritz Daniel Oppenheim]]\n| birth_date         = 14 November 1805\n| birth_place        = Hamburg, Germany\n| death_date         = 14 May 1847\n| death_place        = Berlin, Germany\n| occupation         = {{plainlist|\n* Composer\n* Pianist\n}}\n| spouse             = Wilhelm Hensel\n| children           = 1\n}}\n\n'''Fanny Mendelssohn''' (14 November 1805 \u2013 14 May 1847),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Fanny-Mendelssohn |work=Encyclopaedia Britannica |title=Fanny Mendelssohn |accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref> later '''Fanny [C\u00e4cilie] Mendelssohn Bartholdy''' and, after her marriage, '''Fanny Hensel''', was a German composer and pianist from the [[Romantic era]]. She grew up in Berlin, Germany and received a thorough musical education from teachers including her mother, [[Ludwig Berger (composer)|Ludwig Berger]], and [[Carl Friedrich Zelter]]. Her brother [[Felix Mendelssohn]], also a composer and pianist, shared the same education and the two developed a close relationship. Due to social expectations for women at the time discouraging the publication of her compositions, a number of her works were published under her brother's name in his [[Opus number|Opus]] 8 and 9 collections. In 1829, she married painter [[Wilhelm Hensel]] and, in 1820, the two had a single child, Sebastian Hensel. In 1846, despite the ambivalence of her family towards her musical ambitions, Fanny Hensel published a collection of songs as her Opus 1. The next year, she suddenly died of a stroke.\n\nShe composed over 460 pieces of music, including a [[piano trio]], a [[piano quartet]], an orchestral overture, four cantatas, over 125 pieces for the piano, and an excess of 250 [[Lied|Lieder]], most of which went unpublished in her lifetime. New details about her life and works have been identified since the 1990s. Her ''[[Easter Sonata]]'' was inaccurately credited to her brother in 1970, before analysis of new documents in 2010 corrected the error.  \n\nThe [[Fanny & Felix Mendelssohn Museum]] opened on May 29, 2018 in Hamburg, Germany.\n\n==Life==\n=== Early life and education ===\nMendelssohn was born in [[Hamburg]], the [[Mendelssohn family|oldest of four children]], including the composer Felix Mendelssohn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|title=Hensel [n\u00e9e Mendelssohn (-Bartholdy)], Fanny C\u00e4cilie|website=Grove Music Online|language=en|doi=10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> She was descended on both sides from distinguished [[Jewish]] families; her parents were [[Abraham Mendelssohn]] (who was the son of philosopher [[Moses Mendelssohn]] and later changed the family surname to Mendelssohn Bartholdy), and Lea, n\u00e9e Salomon, a granddaughter of the entrepreneur [[Daniel Itzig]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=3-5|oclc=301705955}}</ref> Her uncle was the banker [[Joseph Mendelssohn]]. She was baptised as a Christian in 1816, becoming Fanny C\u00e4cilia Mendelssohn Bartholdy.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/900353151|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-936639-X|oclc=900353151}}</ref> Despite this, she and her family continued to closely hold the values of Judaism.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805-1847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809\u20131847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=xxix; 629|oclc=11518779}}</ref><ref>Citron (1994), p. 322</ref>\n\n[[File:Fannymendelssohn-improved.jpg|thumb|upright|Fanny Mendelssohn, sketched by her future husband [[Wilhelm Hensel]]]]\nWhile growing up in the family's new home in Berlin,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Forney|first=Kristine|title=The Enjoyment of Music: Essential Listening Edition with Total Access. 12th Edition.|last2=Dell'Antonio|last3=Machlis|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2015|isbn=978-0-393-90604-2|location=|pages=278}}</ref> Mendelssohn showed prodigious musical ability and began to write music. She received her first piano instruction from her mother, who had learned the Berliner-Bach tradition through the writings of [[Johann Kirnberger]], a student of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|oclc=301705955}}</ref> Thus as a 14 year old, Mendelssohn could already play all 24 preludes from Bach's ''[[The Well-Tempered Clavier]]'' from memory alone, and she did so in honour of her father's birthday in 1819.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hayman|first=Sheila|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/mar/08/fanny-mendelssohn-easter-sonata-premiere-sheila-hayman|title=A Fanny Mendelssohn masterpiece finally gets its due|date=2017-03-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Beyond inspiration from her mother, Mendelssohn may also have been influenced by the role-models of her great-aunts [[Fanny von Arnstein]] and [[Itzig family#Sarah Itzig|Sarah Levy]], both lovers of music, the former the patroness of a well-known [[Salon (gathering)|salon]] and the latter a skilled keyboard player in her own right.<ref>Citron, ''Mendelssohn, Fanny'' [Grove]</ref> \n\nAfter studying briefly with the pianist [[Marie Bigot]] in Paris,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805-1847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809-1847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=629|oclc=11518779}}</ref> Mendelssohn and her brother Felix received piano lessons from [[Ludwig Berger (composer)|Ludwig Berger]] and composition instruction from [[Carl Friedrich Zelter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cambridge.org/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521106337|title=Mendelssohn's Musical Education|website=www.cambridge.org|publisher=Cambridge University Press|language=en|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=Sep 2011|title=Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|journal=Journal of Musicological Research|language=en|volume=30|issue=3|pages=178|doi=10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|issn=0141-1896|via=}}</ref> At one point, Zelter favoured Fanny over Felix: he wrote to [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]] in 1816, in a letter introducing Abraham Mendelssohn to the poet, 'He has adorable children and his oldest daughter could give you something of Sebastian Bach. This child is really something special'.<ref>Conway (2011), 171</ref> Both Mendelssohn and her brother Felix received instruction in composition from Zelter starting in 1819.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cambridge.org/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521106337|title=Mendelssohn's Musical Education|website=www.cambridge.org|publisher=Cambridge University Press|language=en|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref> In 1820, they joined the [[Sing-Akademie zu Berlin]], which was led by Zelter at the time.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805\u20131847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809\u20131847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=629|oclc=11518779}}</ref> Much later, in an 1831 letter to Goethe, Zelter described Fanny's skill as a pianist with the highest praise for a woman at the time: \"She plays like a man.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=151|oclc=301705955}}</ref>\t\nVisitors to the Mendelssohn household in the early 1820s, including [[Ignaz Moscheles]] and [[George Thomas Smart|Sir George Smart]], were equally impressed by both siblings.<ref>Conway (2011), p. 169</ref><ref>Smart (1907), pp. 173, 179</ref>\n\n=== Gender limitations ===\nIn the words of the music historian Kristine Forny, at this period \"social assumptions about women long discouraged them from composing (and limited their public performances)\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Forny|first=Kristine|title=The Enjoyment of Music: Essential Listening Edition with Total Access. Twelfth Edition.|last2=Dell'Antonio|first2=Andrew|last3=Machlis|first3=Joseph|publisher=W. W. & Norton & Company|year=2015|isbn=978-0-393-90604-2|location=|pages=276}}</ref> Such attitudes were shared by Mendelssohn's father, who was tolerant, rather than supportive, of her activities as a composer. In 1820, he wrote to her, \"Music will perhaps become his [i.e. Felix's] profession, while for ''you'' it can and must be only an ornament\".<ref>Letter of 16 July 1820, in Hensel (1884), I 82</ref> Although Felix was privately broadly supportive of her as a composer and a performer, he was cautious (professedly for family reasons) of her publishing her works under her own name. He wrote:\n<blockquote>From my knowledge of Fanny I should say that she has neither inclination nor vocation for authorship. She is too much all that a woman ought to be for this. She regulates her house, and neither thinks of the public nor of the musical world, nor even of music at all, until her first duties are fulfilled. Publishing would only disturb her in these, and I cannot say that I approve of it.<ref>Letter to Lea Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, 24 June 1837. Mendelssohn (1864), p. 113\n</ref>  </blockquote>\n\nFelix did arrange with Mendelssohn for some of her songs to be published under his name,<ref name=Hensel>Hensel (1884), II 168\u201371</ref> three in his Op. 8 collection,<ref name=Todd175>Todd (2003), p. 175</ref> and three more in his Op. 9.<ref>Todd (2003), p. 224</ref> In 1842, this resulted in an embarrassing moment when [[Queen Victoria]], receiving Felix at Buckingham Palace, expressed her intention of singing to the composer her favourite of his songs, \"Italien\" (to words by [[Franz Grillparzer]]), which Felix confessed was by Mendelssohn.<ref name=Hensel/><ref name=Todd175/>\n\nThe siblings' bond was strengthened by their shared passion for music. This resulted in musical correspondence between the two. Mendelssohn helped Felix by providing constructive criticism of pieces and projects, which he always considered very carefully.<ref name=\"post972\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/style/1997/03/09/women-of-historic-note/259adb97-9eaf-41ef-94e7-d92b7ca54f04/ \"Women of Historic Note\"]. ''Washington Post'', By Gayle Worl 9 March 1997</ref> Felix would even rework pieces solely based on the suggestions she made and nicknamed her \"Minerva\" after the Roman goddess of wisdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200156440/|title=Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel, 1805\u20131847|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Their correspondence of 1840/41 reveals that they were both outlining scenarios for an opera on the subject of the [[Nibelungenlied]]: Mendelssohn wrote 'The hunt with Siegfried's death provides a splendid finale to the second act'.<ref>Letter of 9 December 1840. See Fanny Mendelssohn (1987), pp. 299\u2013301</ref>\n\nFelix Mendelssohn's friend [[Henry Chorley]] wrote of her: \"Had Madame Hensel been a poor man's daughter, she must have become known to the world by the side of [[Clara Schumann|Madame Schumann]] and [[Marie Pleyel|Madame Pleyel]] as a female pianist of the highest class\"; suggesting that her class was at least as limiting for her career as her sex.<ref>Conway (2011) pp. 27\u201328</ref>\n\n[[File:Fannyhenselgrave.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Grave of Fanny Hensel in Berlin]]For most of her life, Mendelssohn adhered to social expectations despite her underlying desire to publish, only using her musical abilities for private performances and to assist Felix's work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|title=Hensel [n\u00e9e Mendelssohn (-Bartholdy)], Fanny C\u00e4cilie|website=Grove Music Online|language=en|doi=10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n=== Later Life and Death ===\nIn 1829, after a courtship of several years, Fanny married the painter [[Wilhelm Hensel]] and the following year she had her only child, {{ill|Sebastian Hensel|de|Sebastian Hensel (Landwirt)|lt=Sebastian Ludwig Felix Hensel}}.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Halstead|first1=Jill|title=Fanny Mendelssohn: Her Life and Music|url=http://musicforpianos.com/fannylifemusic.htm|website=Music for Pianos|accessdate=8 November 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113101839/http://musicforpianos.com/fannylifemusic.htm|archivedate=13 November 2013|location=Liverpool, UK|date=March 1998}}</ref> \n\nSubsequently, her works were often played alongside her brother's at the family home in Berlin in a Sunday concert series (Sonntagskonzerte), which was originally organised by Fanny's father, and after 1831 carried on by Fanny herself.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805\u20131847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809\u20131847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=631|oclc=11518779}}</ref>\n\nWilhelm was supportive of Fanny's composing and contrasted the other prominent men in her life by recommending that she publish her works.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kimber|first=Marian Wilson|date=Fall 2002|title=The \"Suppression\" of Fanny Mendelssohn: Rethinking Feminist Biography|url=http://ncm.ucpress.edu/cgi/doi/10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|journal=19th-Century Music|language=en|volume=26|issue=2|pages=116|doi=10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|issn=0148-2076|via=}}</ref> Her public debut at the piano (one of only three known public performances according to Mendelssohn scholar Larry Todd)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=x|oclc=301705955}}</ref> came in 1838, when she played her brother's [[Piano Concerto No. 1 (Mendelssohn)|Piano Concerto No. 1]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805\u20131847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809\u20131847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=xxiv|oclc=11518779}}</ref> \n\nIn 1846, she decided, after an approach by two Berlin publishers,<ref>Hensel (1874), v. 2, p. 325</ref> and without consulting Felix, to publish a collection of her songs (as her Op. 1).<ref>Citron, ''Mendelssohn, Fanny''</ref> After publication, Felix wrote to her \"[I] send you my professional blessing on becoming a member of the craft [...] may you have much happiness in giving pleasure to others; may you taste only the sweets and none of the bitterness of authorship; may the public pelt you with roses, and never with sand.\" (12 August 1846). On 14 August Fanny wrote in her journal \"Felix has written, and given me his professional blessing in the kindest manner. I know that he is not quite satisfied in his heart of hearts, but I am glad he has said a kind word to me about it.\" <ref>Hensel (1874), v. 2, pp. 325\u2013326</ref>\n\nFanny Mendelssohn Hensel died in Berlin in on 14 May 1847 of complications from a stroke suffered while rehearsing one of her brother's [[Cantata|cantatas]], ''[[Die erste Walpurgisnacht|The First Walpurgis Night]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200156440/|title=Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel, 1805\u20131847|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Fanny-Mendelssohn|title=Fanny Mendelssohn {{!}} German musician and composer|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Felix himself died less than six months later from the same cause (which was also responsible for the deaths of both of their parents and of their grandfather Moses),<ref>Sterndale Bennett (1955) 376</ref> but not before completing his [[String Quartet No. 6 (Mendelssohn)|String Quartet No. 6 in F minor]], written in memory of his sister.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=348\u2013349|oclc=301705955}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n\n=== Compositions ===\n{{see also|List of compositions by Fanny Mendelssohn}}\nFanny Mendelssohn composed over 460 pieces of music.<ref name=\"post97\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/style/1997/03/09/women-of-historic-note/259adb97-9eaf-41ef-94e7-d92b7ca54f04/ \"Women of Historic Note\"]. ''Washington Post'', By Gayle Worl 9 March 1997</ref> Her compositions include a [[piano trio]], a [[piano quartet]], an orchestral overture, four cantatas, over 125 pieces for the piano, and an excess of 250 Lieder (German art songs).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Forney|first=Kristine|title=The Enjoyment of Music: Essential Listening Edition with Total Access. Twelfth Edition.|last2=Dell'Antonio|first2=Andrew|last3=Machlis|first3=Joseph|publisher=W. W. Norton and Company|year=2014|isbn=978-0-393-90604-2|location=|pages=278}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=April 2011|title=Thinking (and Singing) in Threes|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.30535/mto.17.1.7|journal=Music Theory Online|volume=17|issue=1|pages=2|doi=10.30535/mto.17.1.7|issn=1067-3040|via=}}</ref> A number of her songs were originally published under Felix's name in his [[opus number|opus]] 8 and 9 collections. Her piano works are often in the manner of songs, and many carry the name ''Lied ohne Worte'' (''Song without Words''). This style (and title) of piano music was most successfully developed by Felix Mendelssohn,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mace, Angela Regina|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/852761347|title=Fanny Hensel, Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy, and the Formation of the \"Mendelssohnian\" Style|date=2013|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=118|oclc=852761347}}</ref> though some modern scholars assert that Fanny may have preceded him in the genre.{{fact|date=April 2020}} To differentiate her work, she would often use the title, ''Lied fur Klavier'' (Song for Piano).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mace, Angela Regina|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/852761347|title=Fanny Hensel, Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy, and the Formation of the \"Mendelssohnian\" Style|date=2013|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=118|oclc=852761347}}</ref> \n\nThe majority of Mendelssohn's compositions are limited to Lieder and piano pieces as she felt her abilities did not extend to larger, more intricate compositions. After completing her Quartet, she wrote to Felix in 1835, \"I lack the ability to sustain ideas properly and give them the needed consistency. Therefore Lieder suit me best, in which, if need be, merely a pretty idea without much potential for development can suffice.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805\u20131847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809\u20131847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=174|oclc=11518779}}</ref> She was one of the only women in the world to attempt a string quartet at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|title=Hensel [n\u00e9e Mendelssohn (-Bartholdy)], Fanny C\u00e4cilie|website=Grove Music Online|language=en|doi=10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nShe also wrote, amongst other works for the piano, a cycle of pieces depicting the months of the year,  ''Das Jahr'' (\"The Year\").<ref name=\"grovemusic.com\">Marcia J. Citron: 'Mendelssohn, Fanny', Grove Music Online ed. L. Macy (Accessed [10 June 2008]), <http://www.grovemusic.com> (subscription required)</ref> The music was written on coloured sheets of paper, and illustrated by her husband Wilhelm, with each piece accompanied by a short poem. The writer Kristine Forney has suggested that the poems, artwork and the coloured paper may represent the different stages of life, with some suggesting it represents Mendelssohn's life.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Forney|first=Kristine|title=The Enjoyment of Music: Essential Listening Edition with Total Access. Twelfth Edition|last2=Dell'Antonio|first2=Andrew|last3=Machlis|first3=Joseph|publisher=W. W. Norton and Company|year=2014|isbn=978-0-393-27100-3|location=|pages=277}}</ref> In a letter from Rome, Fanny Mendelssohn described the process behind composing ''Das Jahr'':<blockquote>I have been composing a good deal lately, and have called my piano pieces after the names of my favourite haunts, partly because they really came into my mind at these spots, partly because our pleasant excursions were in my mind while I was writing them. They will form a delightful souvenir, a kind of second diary. But do not imagine that I give these names when playing them in society, they are for home use entirely.<ref>Citron, Marcia J. ''The Letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn.''</ref></blockquote>\n\nAmongst her works is the ''[[Easter Sonata]]'' written in 1828, which was unpublished in her lifetime, then discovered and attributed to her brother in 1970, before examination of the manuscript and a mention of the work in her diary finally established in 2010 that the work was hers.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/03/09/a-mendelssohn-masterpiece-was-really-his-sisters-after-188-years-it-premiered-under-her-name/ \"A Mendelssohn masterpiece was really his sister's. After 188 years, it premiered under her name.\"]. ''Washington Post'', By Derek Hawkins 9 March 2017.</ref> It was premiered in her name on 8 March 2017, [[International Women's Day]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/mar/08/fanny-mendelssohn-easter-sonata-premiere-sheila-hayman \"A Fanny Mendelssohn masterpiece finally gets its due\"]. ''The Guardian'' Sheila Hayman. 8 March 2017</ref>\n\n=== Style and Form ===\nSince the 1990s, Mendelssohn's works and life history has increasingly gained attention, with much of the existing research focusing on her life rather than analyzing the details of her music and its style.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=July 2011|title=Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|journal=Journal of Musicological Research|language=en|volume=30|issue=3|pages=176|doi=10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|issn=0141-1896|via=}}</ref> Angela Mace, the musicologist who proved Mendelssohn's authourship of the ''Easter Sonata,'' has found that Mendelssohn was much more experimental with her Lieder than Felix, noting that her works have a \"harmonic density\" that serves to express emotion.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mace, Angela Regina|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/852761347|title=Fanny Hensel, Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy, and the Formation of the \"Mendelssohnian\" Style|date=2013|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=10|oclc=852761347}}</ref> Musicologist Stephen Rodgers has claimed that the relative lack of analysis of Mendelssohn's music has left the presence of triple hypermeter in her songs mostly overlooked.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=April 2011|title=Thinking (and Singing) in Threes|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.30535/mto.17.1.7|journal=Music Theory Online|volume=17|issue=1|pages=2|doi=10.30535/mto.17.1.7|issn=1067-3040|via=}}</ref> He points to this type of meter being used by Mendelssohn to alter the speed of vocals in the song and to reflect emotions through distortion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=April 2011|title=Thinking (and Singing) in Threes|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.30535/mto.17.1.7|journal=Music Theory Online|volume=17|issue=1|pages=|doi=10.30535/mto.17.1.7|issn=1067-3040|via=}}</ref> He also points to a lack of tonic harmony as a recurring characteristic of her Lieder, identifying it in \"Verlust\" as a deliberate means to reflect the song's themes of abandonment and failing to find love.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=2011-07-01|title=Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|journal=Journal of Musicological Research|volume=30|issue=3|pages=180|doi=10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|issn=0141-1896|via=}}</ref> Mendelssohn's use of [[word painting]] is also acknowledged as common element of her style, being used as a musical method of stressing emotion in the song text.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=2011-07-01|title=Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|journal=Journal of Musicological Research|volume=30|issue=3|pages=175\u2013201|doi=10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|issn=0141-1896}}</ref>\n\nShe commonly used strophic form for her songs and included piano music that moved with the voice, characteristics also held by her teachers Zelter and Berger.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rodgers, Stephen Draper, Brian|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/817677286|title=Text-Painting and Musical Style in the Lieder of Fanny Hensel|publisher=University of Oregon|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=87|oclc=817677286}}</ref> Though the foundation created by her teachers would remain, she increasingly turned to through-composed forms as her style developed as a way to respond to elements of poetic text.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=July 2011|title=Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|journal=Journal of Musicological Research|volume=30|issue=3|pages=201|doi=10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|issn=0141-1896|via=}}</ref> \n\n==Legacy==\nIn the six months before his death, Felix attempted to ensure that his sister received the recognition that had been withheld throughout most of her life by collecting many of her works with the intent of releasing them to the public through his publisher, Breitkopf & Hartel.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=351|oclc=301705955}}</ref> In 1850, the publisher began to distribute Mendelssohn's unreleased works, starting with ''Vier Lieder'' Op. 8.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=351|oclc=301705955}}</ref>\n\nFanny Mendelssohn's only child Sebastian Hensel, father of the philosopher [[Paul Hensel]] and the mathematician [[Kurt Hensel]], played a role in the historical preservation of the Mendelssohn family. He acquired 1,000 portraits from his father Wilhelm's possession, some of which depicted the family.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=356|oclc=301705955}}</ref> He also wrote a three-volume Mendelssohn family history titled ''Die Familie Mendelssohn 1729-1847'' (1879), which chronicled the family up until Fanny and Felix Mendelssohn's deaths.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=354\u2013356|oclc=301705955}}</ref> The two-volume family history has been translated from German to English throughout its many editions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kimber|first=Marian Wilson|date=Fall 2002|title=The \"Suppression\" of Fanny Mendelssohn: Rethinking Feminist Biography|url=http://ncm.ucpress.edu/cgi/doi/10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|journal=[[19th-Century Music]]|volume=26|issue=2|pages=114|doi=10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|issn=0148-2076|via=}}</ref> It was often used as a source of information about Mendelssohn's life by many scholars until new resources emerged.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=356\u2013357|oclc=301705955}}</ref> Though Sebastian's writings were useful to scholars, its purpose was to depict a socially acceptable version of the Mendelssohn family, therefore, it falsely claimed Mendelssohn had no aspirations to perform outside the private sphere.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kimber|first=Marian Wilson|date=Fall 2002|title=The \"Suppression\" of Fanny Mendelssohn: Rethinking Feminist Biography|url=http://ncm.ucpress.edu/cgi/doi/10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|journal=[[19th-Century Music]]|volume=26|issue=2|pages=115|doi=10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|issn=0148-2076|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe Fanny & Felix Mendelssohn Museum, which is dedicated to the lives of and the work of Mendelssohn and her brother Felix, opened on May 29, 2018 in Hamburg, Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.komponistenquartier.de/komponistenquartier/ausstellungen/fanny-and-felix-mendelssohn-museum/|title=Fanny & Felix Mendelssohn Museum \u00bb KomponistenQuartier|website=www.komponistenquartier.de|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, her music has become better known thanks to concert performances and a number of CDs being released on labels such as [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]] and [[Classic Produktion Osnabr\u00fcck|CPO]]. Her reputation has also been advanced by those researching female musical creativity, of which she is one of the relatively few well-documented exemplars in the early 19th century.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} \n\n==References==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Cited Sources ===\n\n* Christian, Angela Mace. \"[https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159 <nowiki>Hensel [N\u00e9e Mendelssohn (-Bartholdy)], Fanny C\u00e4cilie.</nowiki>]\" ''Grove Music Online.'' \n*Citron, Marcia J. \"Mendelssohn(-Bartholdy), Fanny (C\u00e4cilie)\" in ''The New Grove Dictionary of Women Composers''. Macmillan, 1994. {{ISBN|0-333-51598-6}}\n* Conway, David (2011). ''Jewry in Music: Entry to the Profession form the Enlightenment to Richard Wagner''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|9781107015388}}\n*Draper, Brian W. ''Text-Painting and Musical Style in the Lieder of Fanny Hensel'', University of Oregon, Ann Arbor, 2012. ProQuest.\n*\"[https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200156440/ Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel, 1805\u20131847].\" Library of Congress, Washington, D.C.. Retrieved 2020-03-27.\n*Forney, Kristine, et al. ''The Enjoyment of Music: Essential Listening Edition with Total Access.Twelfth Edition''. W. W. Norton & Company, 2015. pp.&nbsp;277-278. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]]&nbsp;[[Special:BookSources/978-0-393-90604-2|<bdi>978-0-393-90604-2</bdi>]].\n*Hawkins, Derek. \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/03/09/a-mendelssohn-masterpiece-was-really-his-sisters-after-188-years-it-premiered-under-her-name/ A Mendelssohn Masterpiece Was Really His Sister's. After 188 Years, It Premiered under Her Name].\" ''The Washington Post'', WP Company, 9 Mar. 2017.\n*Hayman, Sheila. \"[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/mar/08/fanny-mendelssohn-easter-sonata-premiere-sheila-hayman A Fanny Mendelssohn Masterpiece Finally Gets Its Due].\" ''The Guardian'', Guardian News and Media, 8 March 2017.\n* Hensel, Sebastian (ed.) (1884) (tr. Carl Klingemann) ''The Mendelssohn Family (1729\u20131847) From Letters and Journals.'' 2 vols. London: Sampson Low.\n* Kimber, Marian Wilson, \"The 'Suppression' of Fanny Mendelssohn: Rethinking Feminist Biography,\" ''[[19th-Century Music]]'', Vol. 26, No. 2 (Autumn, 2002), pp.&nbsp;113\u2013129.\n*\"[http://www.komponistenquartier.de/komponistenquartier/ausstellungen/fanny-and-felix-mendelssohn-museum/ KomponistenQuartierHamburg.]\" ''Fanny & Felix Mendelssohn Museum  KomponistenQuartier''.\n* Mace, Angela R. ''Fanny Hensel, Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy, and the Formation of the Mendelssohnian Style'', Duke University, Ann Arbor, 2013''. ProQuest''.\n* Mendelssohn Bartholdy, Felix, ed. Paul Mendelssohn Bartholdy, tr. Lady Wallace. ''Letters of Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy from 1833 to 1847'', Longman Green, London 1864.\n* Mendelssohn (Hensel), Fanny, tr. and  ed. Marica Citron. ''The Letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn'' (New York, 1987) {{ISBN|0-918728-52-5}}.\n*[http://www.cambridge.org/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521106337 \"Mendelssohn's Musical Education\"]. ''Cambridge University Press.'' Retrieved 24 January 2017.\n* Rodgers, Stephen, \"Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic.\" ''Journal of Musicological Research''. Vol. 30, Issue 3, (Sep. 2011).\n* Rodgers, Stephen Draper, Brian. ''Text-Painting and Musical Style in the Lieder of Fanny Hensel''. University of Oregon. p. 87.\n* Rodgers, Stephen. \"Thinking (and Singing) in Threes.\" ''Music Theory Online'', vol. 17, no. 1, Apr. 2011, doi:10.30535/mto.17.1.7.\n* Smart, Sir George, ed. H. B. and C. L. E. Cox, ''Leaves from the Journal of Sir George Smart'', London: Longmans, Green and Co.\n* Sterndale Bennett, R., \"The Death of Mendelssohn\", in ''Music and Letters'' vol. 36 no.4, Oxford, 1955.\n*The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica. \"[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Fanny-Mendelssohn Fanny Mendelssohn].\" ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc., 19 Mar. 2020.\n* Todd, R. Larry, ''Fanny Hensel:  The Other Mendelssohn'' (Oxford University Press, 2010) {{ISBN|978-0-19-518080-0}}.\n* Todd, R. Larry, ''Mendelssohn: A Life in Music'' ([[Oxford University Press]], 2003) {{ISBN|0-19-511043-9}}.\n* Todd, R. Larry, and Felix Mendelssohn-Bartholdy. ''Mendelssohn's Musical Education: a Study and Edition of His Exercises in Composition: Oxford Bodleian Ms. Margaret Deneke Mendelssohn C. 43''. Cambridge University Press, 2009.\n* Worl, Gayle. \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/style/1997/03/09/women-of-historic-note/259adb97-9eaf-41ef-94e7-d92b7ca54f04/ Women of Historic Note].\" ''The Washington Post'', WP Company, 9 Mar. 1997.\n\n=== Further reading ===\n*Tillard, Fran\u00e7oise, translated by Camille Naish, ''Fanny Mendelssohn ,'' Amdeus Press, Portland, Oregon, c1996, {{ISBN|0-931340-96-9}}.\n\n===External Links===\n*[http://www.kapralova.org/journal9.pdf Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel: A Life of Music within Domestic Limits] by Eugene Gates, ''Kapralova Society Journal''.\n* [http://www.kapralova.org/journal27.pdf  Influence, Individuality and Stylistic Evolution in the Music of Fanny Hensel and Felix Mendelssohn] by Hye-Bin Song, ''Kapralova Society Journal''.\n* {{IMSLP|id=Hensel, Fanny}}\n* {{ChoralWiki|Fanny Hensel}}\n* [https://musescore.com/openscore-lieder-corpus/sets?order=title&text=hensel Free digital scores by Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel] in the [https://musescore.com/openscore-lieder-corpus/sets OpenScore Lieder Corpus]\n* [http://fannyhensel.de/ FannyHensel.de] \u2013 comprehensive site (in German)\n* [http://www.rcs-krueger.de/FannyHensel.htm Hensel-Biography] \u2013 some notes about the composer and her family\n* [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/Hensel-Mendelssohn-piano-trio.htm Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel Piano Trio in d minor sound-bites and short bio]\n\n{{Felix Mendelssohn}}\n{{Mendelssohn family}}\n{{Romanticism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mendelssohn, Fanny}}\n[[Category:1805 births]]\n[[Category:1847 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fanny Mendelssohn| ]]\n[[Category:19th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century classical pianists]]\n[[Category:19th-century German composers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Dreifaltigkeitsfriedhof I, Berlin]]\n[[Category:Child classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Composers for piano]]\n[[Category:German Calvinist and Reformed Christians]]\n[[Category:German classical composers]]\n[[Category:German classical pianists]]\n[[Category:German women pianists]]\n[[Category:German female classical composers]]\n[[Category:German people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:German Romantic composers]]\n[[Category:Jewish classical composers]]\n[[Category:Mendelssohn family|Fanny]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Hamburg]]\n[[Category:Women classical pianists]]\n[[Category:19th-century women musicians]]\n[[Category:Female classical composers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|19th-century German pianist and composer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Fanny Mendelssohn\n| image              = Fanny Hensel 1842.jpg\n| caption            = Fanny Hensel, 1842, by [[Moritz Daniel Oppenheim]]\n| birth_date         = 14 November 1805\n| birth_place        = Hamburg, Germany\n| death_date         = 14 May 1847\n| death_place        = Berlin, Germany\n| occupation         = {{plainlist|\n* Composer\n* Pianist\n}}\n| spouse             = Wilhelm Hensel\n| children           = 1\n}}\n\n'''Fanny Mendelssohn''' (14 November 1805 \u2013 14 May 1847),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Fanny-Mendelssohn |work=Encyclopaedia Britannica |title=Fanny Mendelssohn |accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref> later '''Fanny [C\u00e4cilie] Mendelssohn Bartholdy''' and, after her marriage, '''Fanny Hensel''', was a German composer and pianist from the [[Romantic era]]. She grew up in Berlin, Germany and received a thorough musical education from teachers including her mother, [[Ludwig Berger (composer)|Ludwig Berger]], and [[Carl Friedrich Zelter]]. Her brother [[Felix Mendelssohn]], also a composer and pianist, shared the same education and the two developed a close relationship. Due to social expectations for women at the time discouraging the publication of her compositions, a number of her works were published under her brother's name in his [[Opus number|Opus]] 8 and 9 collections. In 1829, she married painter [[Wilhelm Hensel]] and, in 1820, the two had a single child, Sebastian Hensel. In 1846, despite the ambivalence of her family towards her musical ambitions, Fanny Hensel published a collection of songs as her Opus 1. The next year, she suddenly died of a stroke.\n\nShe composed over 460 pieces of music, including a [[piano trio]], a [[piano quartet]], an orchestral overture, four cantatas, over 125 pieces for the piano, and an excess of 250 [[Lied|Lieder]], most of which went unpublished in her lifetime. New details about her life and works have been identified since the 1990s. Her ''[[Easter Sonata]]'' was inaccurately credited to her brother in 1970, before analysis of new documents in 2010 corrected the error.  \n\nThe [[Fanny & Felix Mendelssohn Museum]] opened on May 29, 2018 in Hamburg, Germany.\n\n==Life==\n=== Early life and education ===\nMendelssohn was born in [[Hamburg]], the [[Mendelssohn family|oldest of four children]], including the composer Felix Mendelssohn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|title=Hensel [n\u00e9e Mendelssohn (-Bartholdy)], Fanny C\u00e4cilie|website=Grove Music Online|language=en|doi=10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> She was descended on both sides from distinguished [[Jewish]] families; her parents were [[Abraham Mendelssohn]] (who was the son of philosopher [[Moses Mendelssohn]] and later changed the family surname to Mendelssohn Bartholdy), and Lea, n\u00e9e Salomon, a granddaughter of the entrepreneur [[Daniel Itzig]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=3-5|oclc=301705955}}</ref> Her uncle was the banker [[Joseph Mendelssohn]]. She was baptised as a Christian in 1816, becoming Fanny C\u00e4cilia Mendelssohn Bartholdy.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/900353151|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-936639-X|oclc=900353151}}</ref> Despite this, she and her family continued to closely hold the values of Judaism.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805-1847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809-1847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=xxix; 629|oclc=11518779}}</ref><ref>Citron (1994), p. 322</ref>\n\n[[File:Fannymendelssohn-improved.jpg|thumb|upright|Fanny Mendelssohn, sketched by her future husband [[Wilhelm Hensel]]]]\nWhile growing up in the family's new home in Berlin,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Forney|first=Kristine|title=The Enjoyment of Music: Essential Listening Edition with Total Access. 12th Edition.|last2=Dell\u2019Antonio|last3=Machlis|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2015|isbn=978-0-393-90604-2|location=|pages=278}}</ref> Mendelssohn showed prodigious musical ability and began to write music. She received her first piano instruction from her mother, who had learned the Berliner-Bach tradition through the writings of [[Johann Kirnberger]], a student of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|oclc=301705955}}</ref> Thus as a 14 year old, Mendelssohn could already play all 24 preludes from Bach's ''[[The Well-Tempered Clavier]]'' from memory alone, and she did so in honour of her father's birthday in 1819.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hayman|first=Sheila|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/mar/08/fanny-mendelssohn-easter-sonata-premiere-sheila-hayman|title=A Fanny Mendelssohn masterpiece finally gets its due|date=2017-03-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Beyond inspiration from her mother, Mendelssohn may also have been influenced by the role-models of her great-aunts [[Fanny von Arnstein]] and [[Itzig family#Sarah Itzig|Sarah Levy]], both lovers of music, the former the patroness of a well-known [[Salon (gathering)|salon]] and the latter a skilled keyboard player in her own right.<ref>Citron, ''Mendelssohn, Fanny'' [Grove]</ref> \n\nAfter studying briefly with the pianist [[Marie Bigot]] in Paris,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805-1847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809-1847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=629|oclc=11518779}}</ref> Mendelssohn and her brother Felix received piano lessons from [[Ludwig Berger (composer)|Ludwig Berger]] and composition instruction from [[Carl Friedrich Zelter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cambridge.org/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521106337|title=Mendelssohn's Musical Education|website=www.cambridge.org|publisher=Cambridge University Press|language=en|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=Sep 2011|title=Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|journal=Journal of Musicological Research|language=en|volume=30|issue=3|pages=178|doi=10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|issn=0141-1896|via=}}</ref> At one point, Zelter favoured Fanny over Felix: he wrote to [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]] in 1816, in a letter introducing Abraham Mendelssohn to the poet, 'He has adorable children and his oldest daughter could give you something of Sebastian Bach. This child is really something special'.<ref>Conway (2011), 171</ref> Both Mendelssohn and her brother Felix received instruction in composition from Zelter starting in 1819.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cambridge.org/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521106337|title=Mendelssohn's Musical Education|website=www.cambridge.org|publisher=Cambridge University Press|language=en|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref> In 1820, they joined the [[Sing-Akademie zu Berlin]], which was led by Zelter at the time.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805-1847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809-1847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=629|oclc=11518779}}</ref> Much later, in an 1831 letter to Goethe, Zelter described Fanny's skill as a pianist with the highest praise for a woman at the time: \"She plays like a man.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=151|oclc=301705955}}</ref>\t\nVisitors to the Mendelssohn household in the early 1820s, including [[Ignaz Moscheles]] and [[George Thomas Smart|Sir George Smart]], were equally impressed by both siblings.<ref>Conway (2011), p. 169</ref><ref>Smart (1907), pp. 173, 179</ref>\n\n=== Gender limitations ===\nIn the words of the music historian Kristine Forny, at this period \u201csocial assumptions about women long discouraged them from composing (and limited their public performances)\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|last=Forny|first=Kristine|title=The Enjoyment of Music: Essential Listening Edition with Total Access.Twelfth Edition.|last2=Dell'Antonio|first2=Andrew|last3=Machlis|first3=Joseph|publisher=W. W. & Norton & Company|year=2015|isbn=978-0-393-90604-2|location=|pages=276}}</ref> Such attitudes were shared by Mendelssohn's father, who was tolerant, rather than supportive, of her activities as a composer. In 1820, he wrote to her, \"Music will perhaps become his [i.e. Felix's] profession, while for ''you'' it can and must be only an ornament\".<ref>Letter of 16 July 1820, in Hensel (1884), I 82</ref> Although Felix was privately broadly supportive of her as a composer and a performer, he was cautious (professedly for family reasons) of her publishing her works under her own name. He wrote:\n<blockquote>From my knowledge of Fanny I should say that she has neither inclination nor vocation for authorship. She is too much all that a woman ought to be for this. She regulates her house, and neither thinks of the public nor of the musical world, nor even of music at all, until her first duties are fulfilled. Publishing would only disturb her in these, and I cannot say that I approve of it.<ref>Letter to Lea Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, 24 June 1837. Mendelssohn (1864), p. 113\n</ref>  </blockquote>\n\nFelix did arrange with Mendelssohn for some of her songs to be published under his name,<ref name=Hensel>Hensel (1884), II 168\u201371</ref> three in his Op. 8 collection,<ref name=Todd175>Todd (2003), p. 175</ref> and three more in his Op. 9.<ref>Todd (2003), p. 224</ref> In 1842, this resulted in an embarrassing moment when [[Queen Victoria]], receiving Felix at Buckingham Palace, expressed her intention of singing to the composer her favourite of his songs, \"Italien\" (to words by [[Franz Grillparzer]]), which Felix confessed was by Mendelssohn.<ref name=Hensel/><ref name=Todd175/>\n\nThe siblings' bond was strengthened by their shared passion for music. This resulted in musical correspondence between the two. Mendelssohn helped Felix by providing constructive criticism of pieces and projects, which he always considered very carefully.<ref name=\"post972\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/style/1997/03/09/women-of-historic-note/259adb97-9eaf-41ef-94e7-d92b7ca54f04/ \"Women of Historic Note\"]. ''Washington Post'', By Gayle Worl 9 March 1997</ref> Felix would even rework pieces solely based on the suggestions she made and nicknamed her \"Minerva\" after the Roman goddess of wisdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200156440/|title=Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel, 1805-1847|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Their correspondence of 1840/41 reveals that they were both outlining scenarios for an opera on the subject of the [[Nibelungenlied]]: Mendelssohn wrote 'The hunt with Siegfried's death provides a splendid finale to the second act'.<ref>Letter of 9 December 1840. See Fanny Mendelssohn (1987), pp. 299\u2013301</ref>\n\nFelix Mendelssohn's friend [[Henry Chorley]] wrote of her: \"Had Madame Hensel been a poor man's daughter, she must have become known to the world by the side of [[Clara Schumann|Madame Schumann]] and [[Marie Pleyel|Madame Pleyel]] as a female pianist of the highest class\"; suggesting that her class was at least as limiting for her career as her sex.<ref>Conway (2011) pp. 27-28</ref>\n\n[[File:Fannyhenselgrave.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Grave of Fanny Hensel in Berlin]]For most of her life, Mendelssohn adhered to social expectations despite her underlying desire to publish, only using her musical abilities for private performances and to assist Felix's work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|title=Hensel [n\u00e9e Mendelssohn (-Bartholdy)], Fanny C\u00e4cilie|website=Grove Music Online|language=en|doi=10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n=== Later Life and Death ===\nIn 1829, after a courtship of several years, Fanny married the painter [[Wilhelm Hensel]] and the following year she had her only child, Sebastian Ludwig Felix Hensel.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Halstead|first1=Jill|title=Fanny Mendelssohn: Her Life and Music|url=http://musicforpianos.com/fannylifemusic.htm|website=Music for Pianos|accessdate=8 November 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113101839/http://musicforpianos.com/fannylifemusic.htm|archivedate=13 November 2013|location=Liverpool, UK|date=March 1998}}</ref> \n\nSubsequently, her works were often played alongside her brother's at the family home in Berlin in a Sunday concert series (Sonntagskonzerte), which was originally organised by Fanny's father, and after 1831 carried on by Fanny herself.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805-1847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809-1847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=631|oclc=11518779}}</ref>\n\nWilhelm was supportive of Fanny's composing and contrasted the other prominent men in her life by recommending that she publish her works.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kimber|first=Marian Wilson|date=Fall 2002|title=The \"Suppression\" of Fanny Mendelssohn: Rethinking Feminist Biography|url=http://ncm.ucpress.edu/cgi/doi/10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|journal=19th-Century Music|language=en|volume=26|issue=2|pages=116|doi=10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|issn=0148-2076|via=}}</ref> Her public debut at the piano (one of only three known public performances according to Mendelssohn scholar Larry Todd)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=x|oclc=301705955}}</ref> came in 1838, when she played her brother's [[Piano Concerto No. 1 (Mendelssohn)|Piano Concerto No. 1]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805-1847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809-1847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=xxiv|oclc=11518779}}</ref> \n\nIn 1846, she decided, after an approach by two Berlin publishers,<ref>Hensel (1874), v. 2, p. 325</ref> and without consulting Felix, to publish a collection of her songs (as her Op. 1).<ref>Citron, ''Mendelssohn, Fanny''</ref> After publication, Felix wrote to her \"[I] send you my professional blessing on becoming a member of the craft [...] may you have much happiness in giving pleasure to others; may you taste only the sweets and none of the bitterness of authorship; may the public pelt you with roses, and never with sand.\" (12 August 1846). On 14 August Fanny wrote in her journal \"Felix has written, and given me his professional blessing in the kindest manner. I know that he is not quite satisfied in his heart of hearts, but I am glad he has said a kind word to me about it.\" <ref>Hensel (1874), v. 2, pp. 325-326</ref>\n\nFanny Mendelssohn Hensel died in Berlin in on 14 May 1847 of complications from a stroke suffered while rehearsing one of her brother's [[Cantata|cantatas]], ''[[Die erste Walpurgisnacht|The First Walpurgis Night]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200156440/|title=Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel, 1805-1847|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Fanny-Mendelssohn|title=Fanny Mendelssohn {{!}} German musician and composer|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Felix himself died less than six months later from the same cause (which was also responsible for the deaths of both of their parents and of their grandfather Moses),<ref>Sterndale Bennett (1955) 376</ref> but not before completing his [[String Quartet No. 6 (Mendelssohn)|String Quartet No. 6 in F minor]], written in memory of his sister.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=348-349|oclc=301705955}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n\n=== Compositions ===\n{{see also|List of compositions by Fanny Mendelssohn}}\nFanny Mendelssohn composed over 460 pieces of music.<ref name=\"post97\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/style/1997/03/09/women-of-historic-note/259adb97-9eaf-41ef-94e7-d92b7ca54f04/ \"Women of Historic Note\"]. ''Washington Post'', By Gayle Worl 9 March 1997</ref> Her compositions include a [[piano trio]], a [[piano quartet]], an orchestral overture, four cantatas, over 125 pieces for the piano, and an excess of 250 Lieder (German art songs).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Forney|first=Kristine|title=The Enjoyment of Music: Essential Listening Edition with Total Access. Twelfth Edition.|last2=Dell\u2019Antonio|first2=Andrew|last3=Machlis|first3=Joseph|publisher=W. W. Norton and Company|year=2014|isbn=978-0-393-90604-2|location=|pages=278}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=April 2011|title=Thinking (and Singing) in Threes|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.30535/mto.17.1.7|journal=Music Theory Online|volume=17|issue=1|pages=2|doi=10.30535/mto.17.1.7|issn=1067-3040|via=}}</ref> A number of her songs were originally published under Felix's name in his [[opus number|opus]] 8 and 9 collections. Her piano works are often in the manner of songs, and many carry the name ''Lied ohne Worte'' (''Song without Words''). This style (and title) of piano music was most successfully developed by Felix Mendelssohn,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mace, Angela Regina|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/852761347|title=Fanny Hensel, Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy, and the Formation of the \"Mendelssohnian\" Style|date=2013|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=118|oclc=852761347}}</ref> though some modern scholars assert that Fanny may have preceded him in the genre.{{fact|date=April 2020}} To differentiate her work, she would often use the title, ''Lied fur Klavier'' (Song for Piano).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mace, Angela Regina|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/852761347|title=Fanny Hensel, Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy, and the Formation of the \"Mendelssohnian\" Style|date=2013|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=118|oclc=852761347}}</ref> \n\nThe majority of Mendelssohn\u2019s compositions are limited to Lieder and piano pieces as she felt her abilities did not extend to larger, more intricate compositions. After completing her Quartet, she wrote to Felix in 1835, \u201cI lack the ability to sustain ideas properly and give them the needed consistency. Therefore Lieder suit me best, in which, if need be, merely a pretty idea without much potential for development can suffice.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hensel, Fanny Mendelssohn, 1805-1847.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11518779|title=The letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn|date=1987|publisher=Pendragon Press|others=Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix, 1809-1847., Citron, Marcia J.|year=|isbn=0-918728-52-5|location=[Stuyvesant, N.Y.]|pages=174|oclc=11518779}}</ref> She was one of the only women in the world to attempt a string quartet at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|title=Hensel [n\u00e9e Mendelssohn (-Bartholdy)], Fanny C\u00e4cilie|website=Grove Music Online|language=en|doi=10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nShe also wrote, amongst other works for the piano, a cycle of pieces depicting the months of the year,  ''Das Jahr'' (\"The Year\").<ref name=\"grovemusic.com\">Marcia J. Citron: 'Mendelssohn, Fanny', Grove Music Online ed. L. Macy (Accessed [10 June 2008]), <http://www.grovemusic.com> (subscription required)</ref> The music was written on coloured sheets of paper, and illustrated by her husband Wilhelm, with each piece accompanied by a short poem. The writer Kristine Forney has suggested that the poems, artwork and the coloured paper may represent the different stages of life, with some suggesting it represents Mendelssohn's life.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Forney|first=Kristine|title=The Enjoyment of Music: Essential Listening Edition with Total Access. Twelfth Edition|last2=Dell\u2019Antonio|first2=Andrew|last3=Machlis|first3=Joseph|publisher=W. W. Norton and Company|year=2014|isbn=978-0-393-27100-3|location=|pages=277}}</ref> In a letter from Rome, Fanny Mendelssohn described the process behind composing ''Das Jahr'':<blockquote>I have been composing a good deal lately, and have called my piano pieces after the names of my favourite haunts, partly because they really came into my mind at these spots, partly because our pleasant excursions were in my mind while I was writing them. They will form a delightful souvenir, a kind of second diary. But do not imagine that I give these names when playing them in society, they are for home use entirely.<ref>Citron, Marcia J. ''The Letters of Fanny Hensel to Felix Mendelssohn.''</ref></blockquote>\n\nAmongst her works is the ''[[Easter Sonata]]'' written in 1828, which was unpublished in her lifetime, then discovered and attributed to her brother in 1970, before examination of the manuscript and a mention of the work in her diary finally established in 2010 that the work was hers.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/03/09/a-mendelssohn-masterpiece-was-really-his-sisters-after-188-years-it-premiered-under-her-name/ \"A Mendelssohn masterpiece was really his sister\u2019s. After 188 years, it premiered under her name.\"]. ''Washington Post'', By Derek Hawkins 9 March 2017.</ref> It was premiered in her name on 8 March 2017, [[International Women's Day]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/mar/08/fanny-mendelssohn-easter-sonata-premiere-sheila-hayman \"A Fanny Mendelssohn masterpiece finally gets its due\"]. ''The Guardian'' Sheila Hayman. 8 March 2017</ref>\n\n=== Style and Form ===\nSince the 1990s, Mendelssohn\u2019s works and life history has increasingly gained attention, with much of the existing research focusing on her life rather than analyzing the details of her music and its style.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=July 2011|title=Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|journal=Journal of Musicological Research|language=en|volume=30|issue=3|pages=176|doi=10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|issn=0141-1896|via=}}</ref> Angela Mace, the musicologist who proved Mendelssohn's authourship of the ''Easter Sonata,'' has found that Mendelssohn was much more experimental with her Lieder than Felix, noting that her works have a \"harmonic density\" that serves to express emotion.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mace, Angela Regina|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/852761347|title=Fanny Hensel, Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy, and the Formation of the \"Mendelssohnian\" Style|date=2013|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=10|oclc=852761347}}</ref> Musicologist Stephen Rodgers has claimed that the relative lack of analysis of Mendelssohn\u2019s music has left the presence of triple hypermeter in her songs mostly overlooked.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=April 2011|title=Thinking (and Singing) in Threes|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.30535/mto.17.1.7|journal=Music Theory Online|volume=17|issue=1|pages=2|doi=10.30535/mto.17.1.7|issn=1067-3040|via=}}</ref> He points to this type of meter being used by Mendelssohn to alter the speed of vocals in the song and to reflect emotions through distortion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=April 2011|title=Thinking (and Singing) in Threes|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.30535/mto.17.1.7|journal=Music Theory Online|volume=17|issue=1|pages=|doi=10.30535/mto.17.1.7|issn=1067-3040|via=}}</ref> He also points to a lack of tonic harmony as a recurring characteristic of her Lieder, identifying it in \"Verlust\" as a deliberate means to reflect the song's themes of abandonment and failing to find love.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=2011-07-01|title=Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|journal=Journal of Musicological Research|volume=30|issue=3|pages=180|doi=10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|issn=0141-1896|via=}}</ref> Mendelssohn's use of [[word painting]] is also acknowledged as common element of her style, being used as a musical method of stressing emotion in the song text.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=2011-07-01|title=Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|journal=Journal of Musicological Research|volume=30|issue=3|pages=175\u2013201|doi=10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|issn=0141-1896}}</ref>\n\nShe commonly used strophic form for her songs and included piano music that moved with the voice, characteristics also held by her teachers Zelter and Berger.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rodgers, Stephen Draper, Brian|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/817677286|title=Text-Painting and Musical Style in the Lieder of Fanny Hensel|publisher=University of Oregon|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=87|oclc=817677286}}</ref> Though the foundation created by her teachers would remain, she increasingly turned to through-composed forms as her style developed as a way to respond to elements of poetic text.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodgers|first=Stephen|date=July 2011|title=Fanny Hensel's Lied Aesthetic|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|journal=Journal of Musicological Research|volume=30|issue=3|pages=201|doi=10.1080/01411896.2011.588641|issn=0141-1896|via=}}</ref> \n\n==Legacy==\nIn the six months before his death, Felix attempted to ensure that his sister received the recognition that had been withheld throughout most of her life by collecting many of her works with the intent of releasing them to the public through his publisher, Breitkopf & Hartel.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=351|oclc=301705955}}</ref> In 1850, the publisher began to distribute Mendelssohn\u2019s unreleased works, starting with ''Vier Lieder'' Op. 8.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=351|oclc=301705955}}</ref>\n\nFanny Mendelssohn's only child Sebastian Hensel, father of the philosopher [[Paul Hensel]] and the mathematician [[Kurt Hensel]], played a role in the historical preservation of the Mendelssohn family. He acquired 1,000 portraits from his father Wilhelm\u2019s possession, some of which depicted the family.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=356|oclc=301705955}}</ref> He also wrote a three-volume Mendelssohn family history titled ''Die Familie Mendelssohn 1729-1847'' (1879), which chronicled the family up until Fanny and Felix Mendelssohn's deaths.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=354-356|oclc=301705955}}</ref> The two-volume family history has been translated from German to English throughout its many editions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kimber|first=Marian Wilson|date=Fall 2002|title=The \"Suppression\" of Fanny Mendelssohn: Rethinking Feminist Biography|url=http://ncm.ucpress.edu/cgi/doi/10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|journal=19th-Century Music|language=en|volume=26|issue=2|pages=114|doi=10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|issn=0148-2076|via=}}</ref> It was often used as a source of information about Mendelssohn\u2019s life by many scholars until new resources emerged.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Todd, R. Larry.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/301705955|title=Fanny Hensel : the other Mendelssohn|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-518080-0|location=New York|pages=356-357|oclc=301705955}}</ref> Though Sebastian\u2019s writings were useful to scholars, its purpose was to depict a socially acceptable version of the Mendelssohn family, therefore, it falsely claimed Mendelssohn had no aspirations to perform outside the private sphere.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kimber|first=Marian Wilson|date=Fall 2002|title=The \"Suppression\" of Fanny Mendelssohn: Rethinking Feminist Biography|url=http://ncm.ucpress.edu/cgi/doi/10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|journal=19th-Century Music|language=en|volume=26|issue=2|pages=115|doi=10.1525/ncm.2002.26.2.113|issn=0148-2076|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe Fanny & Felix Mendelssohn Museum, which is dedicated to the lives of and the work of Mendelssohn and her brother Felix, opened on May 29, 2018 in Hamburg, Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.komponistenquartier.de/komponistenquartier/ausstellungen/fanny-and-felix-mendelssohn-museum/|title=Fanny & Felix Mendelssohn Museum \u00bb KomponistenQuartier|website=www.komponistenquartier.de|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, her music has become better known thanks to concert performances and a number of CDs being released on labels such as [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]] and [[Classic Produktion Osnabr\u00fcck|CPO]]. Her reputation has also been advanced by those researching female musical creativity, of which she is one of the relatively few well-documented exemplars in the early 19th century.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} \n\n==References==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Cited Sources ===\n\n* Christian, Angela Mace. \u201c[https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-3000000159 <nowiki>Hensel [N\u00e9e Mendelssohn (-Bartholdy)], Fanny C\u00e4cilie.</nowiki>]\u201d ''Grove Music Online.'' \n*Citron, Marcia J. \"Mendelssohn(-Bartholdy), Fanny (C\u00e4cilie)\" in ''The New Grove Dictionary of Women Composers''. Macmillan, 1994. {{ISBN|0-333-51598-6}}\n* Conway, David (2011). ''Jewry in music: Entry to the Profession form the Enlightenment to Richard Wagner''. Cambridge: Cambriodge University Press. {{ISBN|9781107015388}}\n*Draper, Brian W. ''Text-Painting and Musical Style in the Lieder of Fanny Hensel'', University of Oregon, Ann Arbor, 2012''. ProQuest.''\n*\"[https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200156440/ Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel, 1805-1847].\" ''Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA''. Retrieved 2020-03-27.\n*Forney, Kristine, et al. ''The Enjoyment of Music: Essential Listening Edition with Total Access.Twelfth Edition''. W. W. Norton & Company, 2015. pp.&nbsp;277-278. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]]&nbsp;[[Special:BookSources/978-0-393-90604-2|<bdi>978-0-393-90604-2</bdi>]].\n*Hawkins, Derek. \u201c[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/03/09/a-mendelssohn-masterpiece-was-really-his-sisters-after-188-years-it-premiered-under-her-name/ A Mendelssohn Masterpiece Was Really His Sister's. After 188 Years, It Premiered under Her Name].\u201d ''The Washington Post'', WP Company, 9 Mar. 2017.\n*Hayman, Sheila. \u201c[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/mar/08/fanny-mendelssohn-easter-sonata-premiere-sheila-hayman A Fanny Mendelssohn Masterpiece Finally Gets Its Due].\u201d ''The Guardian'', Guardian News and Media, 8 Mar. 2017.\n* Henselt, Sebastian (ed.) (1884) (tr. Carl Klingemann) ''The Mendelssohn Family (1729-1847) From Letters and Journals.'' 2 vols. London: Sampson Low.\n* Kimber, Marian Wilson, \"The 'Suppression' of Fanny Mendelssohn: Rethinking Feminist Biography,\" 19th-Century Music, Vol. 26, No. 2 (Autumn, 2002), pp.&nbsp;113\u2013